# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nobel-prize
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The **14th Dalai Lama** (born **Lhamo Thondup**; 6 July 1935; full spiritual name: **Jetsun Jamphel Ngawang Lobsang Yeshe Tenzin Gyatso**, shortened as **Tenzin Gyatso**) is the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He served as the resident spiritual and temporal leader of Tibet before 1959, and subsequently led the Tibetan government in exile represented by the Central Tibetan Administration in Dharamshala, India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] A belief central to the Tibetan Buddhist tradition as well as the institution of the Dalai Lama is that the reincarnated person is a living Bodhisattva, specifically an emanation of Avalokiteśvara (in Sanskrit) or Chenrezig (in Tibetan), the Bodhisattva of Compassion.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Mongolic word *dalai* means *ocean.* The 14th Dalai Lama is also known to Tibetans as **Gyalwa Rinpoche** ("The Precious Jewel-like Buddha-Master"), *Kundun* ("The Presence"), and *Yizhin Norbu* ("The Wish-Fulfilling Gem").
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His devotees, as well as much of the Western world, often call him ***His Holiness the Dalai Lama***.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He is the leader and a monk of the newest Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama was born to a farming family in Taktser (*Hongya* village), in the traditional Tibetan region of Amdo, at the time a Chinese frontier district.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was selected as the tulku of the 13th Dalai Lama in 1937, and formally recognised as the 14th Dalai Lama in 1939.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As with the recognition process for his predecessor, a Golden Urn selection process was waived and approved by the Nationalist government of China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His enthronement ceremony was held in Lhasa on 22 February 1940.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following the Battle of Chamdo, in which PRC forces annexed Central Tibet, the Tibetan government, the Ganden Phodrang, invested the Dalai Lama with temporal duties on 17 November 1950 (at 15 years of age), which he held until his exile in 1959.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] During the 1959 Tibetan uprising, the Dalai Lama escaped to India, where he continues to live.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 29 April 1959, the Dalai Lama established the independent Tibetan government in exile in the north Indian hill station of Mussoorie, which then moved in May 1960 to Dharamshala, where he resides.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He retired as political head in 2011 to make way for a democratic government, the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama advocates for the welfare of Tibetans and since the early 1970s has called for the Middle Way Approach with China to peacefully resolve the issue of Tibet.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He criticised the CIA Tibetan program, saying that its sudden end in 1972 proved it was primarily aimed at serving American interests.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Up until his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama travelled worldwide to give Tibetan Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism teachings, and his Kalachakra teachings and initiations were international events.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He also attended conferences on a wide range of subjects, including the relationship between religion and science, met with other world leaders, religious leaders, philosophers, and scientists, online and in-person.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Since 2018, he has continued to teach on a reduced schedule, limiting his travel to within India only, and occasionally addressing international audiences via live webcasts.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His work includes focus on the environment, economics, women's rights, nonviolence, interfaith dialogue, physics, astronomy, Buddhism and science, cognitive neuroscience, reproductive health and sexuality.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] *Time* magazine named the Dalai Lama Gandhi's spiritual heir to nonviolence.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In addition, an Indian MP delegation led by Sujeet Kumar, Member of Parliament, Rajya Sabha has advocated for the Dalai Lama to receive the Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour in India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Lhamo Thondup was born on 6 July 1935, to Choekyong Tsering and his wife Dekyi Tsering, a farming and horse trading family in the small hamlet of Taktser under the control of the Ma clique loyal to the Republic of China as part of Qinghai and on the edge of the traditionally Tibetan region of Amdo.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was one of seven siblings to survive childhood and one of the three supposed reincarnated Rinpoches in the same family.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest sister, Tsering Dolma, was 16 years his senior and was midwife to his mother at his birth.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] She would accompany him into exile and found Tibetan Children's Villages.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest brother, Thupten Jigme Norbu, had been recognised at the age of three by the 13th Dalai Lama as the reincarnation of the high Lama, the 6th Taktser Rinpoche.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His fifth brother, Tendzin Choegyal, had been recognised as the 16th Ngari Rinpoche.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His sister, Jetsun Pema, spent most of her adult life on the Tibetan Children's Villages project.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama has said that his first language was "a broken Xining language which was (a dialect of) the Chinese language, a form of Central Plains Mandarin", and his family speaks neither Amdo Tibetan nor Lhasa Tibetan.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] After the demise of the 13th Dalai Lama, in 1935, the Ordinance of Lama Temple Management was published by the Central Government.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1936, the Method of Reincarnation of Lamas was published by the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission of the Central Government.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 3 states that death of lamas, including the Dalai Lama and Panchen Lama, should be reported to the commission, soul boys should be located and checked by the commission, and a lot-drawing ceremony with the Golden Urn system should be held.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 6 states that local governments should invite officials from the Central Government to take care of the sitting-in-the-bed ceremony.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 7 states that soul boys should not be sought from current lama families.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This article echoes what the Qianlong Emperor described in The Discourse of Lama to eliminate greedy families with multiple reincarnated rinpoches, lamas.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Based on custom and regulation, the regent was actively involved in the search for the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following reported signs and visions, three search teams were sent out to the north-east, the east, and the south-east to locate the new incarnation when the boy who was to become the 14th Dalai Lama was about two years old.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Sir Basil Gould, British delegate to Lhasa in 1936, related his account of the north-eastern team to Sir Charles Alfred Bell, former British resident in Lhasa and friend of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Among other omens, the head of the embalmed body of the 13th Dalai Lama, at first facing south-east, had turned to face the north-east, indicating, it was interpreted, the direction in which his successor would be found.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Regent, Reting Rinpoche, shortly afterwards had a vision at the sacred lake of Lhamo La-tso which he interpreted as Amdo being the region to search.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This vision was also interpreted to refer to a large monastery with a gilded roof and turquoise tiles, and a twisting path from there to a hill to the east, opposite which stood a small house with distinctive eaves.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The team, led by Kewtsang Rinpoche, went first to meet the Panchen Lama, who had been stuck in Jyekundo, in northern Kham.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Panchen Lama had been investigating births of unusual children in the area ever since the death of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He gave Kewtsang the names of three boys whom he had discovered and identified as candidates.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Within a year the Panchen Lama had died.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two of his three candidates were crossed off the list but the third, a "fearless" child, the most promising, was from Taktser village, which, as in the vision, was on a hill, at the end of a trail leading to Taktser from the great Kumbum Monastery with its gilded, turquoise roof.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] There they found a house, as interpreted from the vision—the house where Lhamo Dhondup lived.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama claims that at the time, the village of Taktser stood right on the "real border" between the region of Amdo and China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the search lore, when the team visited, posing as pilgrims, its leader, a Sera Lama, pretended to be the servant and sat separately in the kitchen.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He held an old mala that had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama, and the boy Lhamo Dhondup, aged two, approached and asked for it.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The monk said, "If you know who I am, you can have it." The child said, "Sera Lama, Sera Lama", and spoke with him in a Lhasa accent, in a dialect the boy's mother could not understand.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The next time the party returned to the house, they revealed their real purpose and asked permission to subject the boy to certain tests.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] One test consisted of showing him various pairs of objects, one of which had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama and one which had not.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In every case, he chose the Dalai Lama's own objects and rejected the others.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] From 1936 the Hui "Ma clique" Muslim warlord Ma Bufang ruled Qinghai as its governor under the nominal authority of the Republic of China central government.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to an interview with the 14th Dalai Lama, in the 1930s, Ma Bufang had seized this north-east corner of Amdo in the name of Chiang Kai-shek's weak government and incorporated it into the Chinese province of Qinghai.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Before going to Taktser, Kewtsang had gone to Ma Bufang to pay his respects.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] When Ma Bufang heard a candidate had been found in Taktser, he had the family brought to him in Xining.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He first demanded proof that the boy was the Dalai Lama, but the Lhasa government, though informed by Kewtsang that this was the one, told Kewtsang to say he had to go to Lhasa for further tests with other candidates.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They knew that if he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, the Chinese government would insist on sending a large army escort with him, which would then stay in Lhasa and refuse to budge.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Ma Bufang, together with Kumbum Monastery, then refused to allow him to depart unless he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, but withdrew this demand in return for 100,000 Chinese dollars ransom in silver to be shared among them, to let them go to Lhasa.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two years of diplomatic wrangling followed before it was accepted by Lhasa that the ransom had to be paid to avoid the Chinese getting involved and escorting him to Lhasa with a large army.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Meanwhile, the boy was kept at Kumbum where two of his brothers were already studying as monks and recognised incarnate lamas.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The payment of 300,000 silver dollars was then advanced by Muslim traders en route to Mecca in a large caravan via Lhasa.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They paid Ma Bufang on behalf of the Tibetan government against promissory notes to be redeemed, with interest, in Lhasa.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 20,000-dollar fee for an escort was dropped, since the Muslim merchants invited them to join their caravan for protection; Ma Bufang sent 20 of his soldiers with them and was paid from both sides since the Chinese government granted him another 50,000 dollars for the expenses of the journey.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Furthermore, the Indian government helped the Tibetans raise the ransom funds by affording them import concessions.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 22 September 1938, representatives of Tibet Office in Beijing informed Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that 3 candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held in Tibet.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In October 1938, the Method of Using Golden Urn for the 14th Dalai Lama was drafted by Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 12 December 1938, regent Jamphel Yeshe Gyaltsen, the serving Reting Rinpoche, informed the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that three candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Released from Kumbum, on 21 July 1939 the party travelled across Tibet on a journey to Lhasa in the large Muslim caravan with Lhamo Dhondup, now four years old, riding with his brother Lobsang in a special palanquin carried by two mules, two years after being discovered.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As soon as they were out of Ma Bufang's area, he was officially declared to be the 14th Dalai Lama by the Kashag, and after ten weeks of travel he arrived in Lhasa on 8 October 1939.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The ordination (pabbajja) and giving of the monastic name of Tenzin Gyatso were arranged by Reting Rinpoche and according to the Dalai Lama "I received my ordination from Kyabjé Ling Rinpoché in the Jokhang in Lhasa." There was very limited Chinese involvement at this time.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The family of the 14th Dalai Lama was elevated to the highest stratum of the Tibetan aristocracy and acquired land and serf holdings, as with the families of previous Dalai Lamas.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1959, at the age of 23, he took his final examination at Lhasa's Jokhang Temple during the annual Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He passed with honours and was awarded the Lharampa degree, the highest-level *geshe* degree, roughly equivalent to a doctorate in Buddhist philosophy.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, he had a succession of tutors in Tibet including Reting Rinpoche, Tathag Rinpoche, Ling Rinpoche and lastly Trijang Rinpoche, who became junior tutor when he was 19.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] At the age of 11 he met the Austrian mountaineer Heinrich Harrer, who became his videographer and tutor about the world outside Lhasa.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The two remained friends until Harrer's death in 2006.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Historically the Dalai Lamas or their regents held political and religious leadership over Tibet from Lhasa with varying degrees of influence depending on the regions of Tibet and periods of history.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This began with the 5th Dalai Lama's rule in 1642 and lasted until the 1950s (except for 1705–1750), during which period the Dalai Lamas headed the Tibetan government or Ganden Phodrang.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until 1912 however, when the 13th Dalai Lama declared the complete independence of Tibet, their rule was generally subject to patronage and protection of firstly Mongol kings (1642–1720) and then the Manchu-led Qing dynasty (1720–1912).
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterwards in 1939, at the age of four, the Dalai Lama was taken in a procession of lamas to Lhasa.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Former British officials stationed in India and Tibet recalled that envoys from Britain and China were present at the Dalai Lama's enthronement in February 1940.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] According to Basil Gould, the Chinese representative Wu Chunghsin was reportedly unhappy about the position he had during the ceremony.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterward an article appeared in the Chinese press falsely claiming that Wu personally announced the installation of the Dalai Lama, who supposedly prostrated himself to Wu in gratitude.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After his enthronement, the Dalai Lama's childhood was then spent between the Potala Palace and Norbulingka, his summer residence, both of which are now UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang Kai Shek ordered Ma Bufang to put his Muslim soldiers on alert for an invasion of Tibet in 1942.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang complied, and moved several thousand troops to the border with Tibet.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang also threatened the Tibetans with aerial bombardment if they worked with the Japanese.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang attacked the Tibetan Buddhist Tsang monastery in 1941.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He also constantly attacked the Labrang monastery.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 1950 the army of the People's Republic of China marched to the edge of the Dalai Lama's territory and sent a delegation after defeating a legion of the Tibetan army in warlord-controlled Kham.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 17 November 1950, at the age of 15, the 14th Dalai Lama assumed full temporal (political) power as ruler of Tibet.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's formal rule as head of the government in Tibet was brief although he was enthroned as spiritual leader on 22 February 1940.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When Chinese cadres entered Tibet in 1950, with a crisis looming, the Dalai Lama was asked to assume the role of head of state at the age of 15, which he did on 17 November 1950.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Customarily the Dalai Lama would typically assume control at about the age of 20.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He sent a delegation to Beijing, which signed the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama believes the draft agreement was written by China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Tibetan representatives were not allowed to suggest any alterations and China did not allow the Tibetan representatives to communicate with the Tibetan government in Lhasa.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan delegation was not authorised by Lhasa to sign, but ultimately submitted to pressure from the Chinese to sign anyway, using seals specifically made for the purpose.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Seventeen Point Agreement recognised Chinese sovereignty over Tibet, but China allowed the Dalai Lama to continue to rule Tibet internally, and it allowed the system of feudal peasantry to persist.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1951, following a lengthy discussion with the returning delegates, the National Assembly recommended that the Dalai Lama accept the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He telegraphed his confirmation to Chairman Mao Zedong on 24 October.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scholar Robert Barnett wrote of the serfdom controversy: "So even if it were agreed that serfdom and feudalism existed in Tibet, this would be little different other than in technicalities from conditions in any other 'premodern' peasant society, including most of China at that time.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The power of the Chinese argument therefore lies in its implication that serfdom, and with it feudalism, is inseparable from extreme abuse.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Evidence to support this linkage has not been found by scholars other than those close to Chinese governmental circles.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The 19-year-old Dalai Lama toured China for almost a year from 1954 to 1955, meeting many of the revolutionary leaders and the top echelon of the Chinese communist leadership who created modern China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He learned Chinese and socialist ideals, as explained by his Chinese hosts, on a tour of China showcasing the benefits of socialism and the effective governance provided to turn the large, impoverished nation into a modern and egalitarian society, which impressed him.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1954, he went to the Chinese capital to meet Chairman Mao Zedong with the 10th Panchen Lama and attend the 1st National People's Congress as a delegate, primarily discussing China's constitution.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 27 September 1954, the Dalai Lama was selected as a Vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, a post he officially held until 1964.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1956, on a trip to India to celebrate the Buddha's Birthday, the Dalai Lama asked the Prime Minister of India, Jawaharlal Nehru, if he would allow him political asylum should he choose to stay.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Nehru discouraged this as a provocation against peace, and reminded him of the Indian Government's non-interventionist stance agreed upon with its 1954 treaty with China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Long called a "splittist" and "traitor" by China, the Dalai Lama has attempted formal talks over Tibet's status in China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Chinese Foreign Ministry has warned the US and other countries to "shun" the Dalai Lama during visits and often uses trade negotiations and human rights talks as an incentive to do so.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] China sporadically bans images of the Dalai Lama and arrests citizens for owning photos of him in Tibet.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In April 2018, the Dalai Lama confirmed Chinese government claims about Gedhun Choekyi Nyima by saying that he knew from "reliable sources" that the Panchen Lama he had recognised was alive and receiving normal education.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He said he hoped that the Chinese-recognised Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is a target of Chinese state sponsored hacking.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Security experts claim "targeting Tibetan activists is a strong indicator of official Chinese government involvement" since economic information is the primary goal of private Chinese hackers.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009 the personal office of the Dalai Lama asked researchers at the Munk Center for International Studies at the University of Toronto to check its computers for malicious software.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] A second cyberspy network, Shadow Network, was discovered by the same researchers in 2010.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Stolen documents included a year's worth of the Dalai Lama's personal email, and classified government material relating to India, West Africa, the Russian Federation, the Middle East, and NATO.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] "Sophisticated" hackers were linked to universities in China, Beijing again denied involvement.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chinese hackers posing as The New York Times, Amnesty International and other organisation's reporters targeted the private office of the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Parliament members, and Tibetan nongovernmental organisations, among others, in 2019.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the outset of the 1959 Tibetan uprising, fearing for his life, the Dalai Lama and his retinue fled Tibet with the help of the CIA's Special Activities Division, crossing into India on 30 March 1959, reaching Tezpur in Assam on 18 April.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Some time later he set up the Government of Tibet in Exile in Dharamshala, India, which is often referred to as "*Little Lhasa*".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After the founding of the government in exile he re-established the approximately 80,000 Tibetan refugees who followed him into exile in agricultural settlements.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He created a Tibetan educational system in order to teach the Tibetan children the language, history, religion, and culture.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan Institute of Performing Arts was established in 1959 and the Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies became the primary university for Tibetans in India in 1967.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He supported the refounding of 200 monasteries and nunneries in an attempt to preserve Tibetan Buddhist teachings and the Tibetan way of life.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama appealed to the United Nations on the rights of Tibetans.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This appeal resulted in three resolutions adopted by the General Assembly in 1959, 1961, and 1965, all before the People's Republic was allowed representation at the United Nations.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The resolutions called on China to respect the human rights of Tibetans.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1963, he promulgated a democratic constitution which is based upon the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, creating an elected parliament and an administration to champion his cause.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1970, he opened the Library of Tibetan Works and Archives in Dharamshala which houses over 80,000 manuscripts and important knowledge resources related to Tibetan history, politics and culture.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] It is considered one of the most important institutions for Tibetology in the world.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2016, there were demands from Indian citizens and politicians of different political parties to confer the Dalai Lama the prestigious Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour of India, which has only been awarded to a non-Indian citizen twice in its history.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2021, it was revealed that the Dalai Lama's inner circle were listed in the Pegasus project data as having been targeted with spyware on their phones.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Analysis strongly indicates potential targets were selected by the Indian government.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2025, Indian Members of Parliament (MPs), led by Sujeet Kumar, BJP Rajya Sabha MP, called for His Holiness to be awarded the Bharat Ratna.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the Congressional Human Rights Caucus in 1987 in Washington, D.C., the Dalai Lama gave a speech outlining his ideas for the future status of Tibet.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan called for Tibet to become a democratic "zone of peace" without nuclear weapons, and with support for human rights.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan would come to be known as the "Strasbourg proposal", because the Dalai Lama expanded on the plan at Strasbourg on 15 June 1988.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] There, he proposed the creation of a self-governing Tibet "in association with the People's Republic of China." This would have been pursued by negotiations with the PRC government, but the plan was rejected by the Tibetan Government-in-Exile in 1991.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has indicated that he wishes to return to Tibet only if the People's Republic of China agrees not to make any precondition for his return.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In the 1970s, the Paramount leader Deng Xiaoping set China's sole return requirement to the Dalai Lama as that he "must [come back] as a Chinese citizen ... that is, patriotism".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama celebrated his 70th birthday on 6 July 2005.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] About 10,000 Tibetan refugees, monks and foreign tourists gathered outside his home.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Patriarch Alexius II of the Russian Orthodox Church alleged positive relations with Buddhists.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] However, later that year, the Russian state prevented the Dalai Lama from fulfilling an invitation to the traditionally Buddhist republic of Kalmykia.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The President of the Republic of China (Taiwan), Chen Shui-bian, attended an evening celebrating the Dalai Lama's birthday at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall in Taipei.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 2008 in Japan, the Dalai Lama addressed the 2008 Tibetan violence that had erupted and that the Chinese government accused him of fomenting.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He responded that he had "lost faith" in efforts to negotiate with the Chinese government, and that it was "up to the Tibetan people" to decide what to do.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] During his visit to Taiwan after Typhoon Morakot 30 Taiwanese indigenous peoples protested against the Dalai Lama and denounced it as politically motivated.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is an advocate for a world free of nuclear weapons, and serves on the Advisory Council of the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has voiced his support for the Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly, an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until reaching his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama maintained a busy international lecture and teaching schedule.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, he has continued to teach, but has limited his travel to within India only.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] His public talks and teachings are usually webcast live in multiple languages, via an inviting organisation's website, or on the Dalai Lama's own website.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scores of his past teaching videos can be viewed there, as well as public talks, conferences, interviews, dialogues and panel discussions.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's best known teaching subject is the Kalachakra tantra which, as of 2014, he had conferred a total of 33 times, most often in India's upper Himalayan regions but also in the Western world.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) is one of the most complex teachings of Buddhism, sometimes taking two weeks to confer, and he often confers it on very large audiences, up to 200,000 students and disciples at a time.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is the author of numerous books on Buddhism, many of them on general Buddhist subjects but also including books on particular topics like Dzogchen, a Nyingma practice.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, his schedule has contained fewer engagements, with most occurring in India along with a handful webcasts to international audiences.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Again in London in 1996 he taught the Four Noble Truths, the basis and foundation of Buddhism accepted by all Buddhists, at the combined invitation of 27 different Buddhist organisations of all schools and traditions belonging to the Network of Buddhist Organisations UK.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In India, no fees are charged to attend these teachings since costs are covered by requesting sponsors.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When he travels abroad to give teachings there is usually a ticket fee calculated by the inviting organisation to cover the costs involved and any surplus is normally to be donated to recognised charities.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has frequently visited and lectured at colleges and universities, some of which have conferred honorary degrees upon him.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Dozens of videos of recorded webcasts of the Dalai Lama's public talks on general subjects for non-Buddhists like peace, happiness and compassion, modern ethics, the environment, economic and social issues, gender, the empowerment of women and so forth can be viewed in his office's archive.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama met Pope Paul VI at the Vatican in 1973.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1990, he met a delegation of Jewish teachers in Dharamshala for an extensive interfaith dialogue.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has since visited Israel three times, and in 2006 met the Chief Rabbi of Israel.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2006, he met Pope Benedict XVI privately.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has met the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Robert Runcie, and other leaders of the Anglican Church in London, Gordon B.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Hinckley, who at the time was the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as well as senior Eastern Orthodox Church, Muslim, Hindu, Jewish, and Sikh officials.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1996 and 2002, he participated in the first two Gethsemani Encounters hosted by the Monastic Interreligious Dialogue at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani, where Thomas Merton, whom the Dalai Lama had met in the late 1960s, had lived.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He is also a member of the Board of World Religious Leaders as part of The Elijah Interfaith Institute and participated in the Third Meeting of the Board of World Religious Leaders in Amritsar, India, on 26 November 2007 to discuss the topic of Love and Forgiveness.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009, the Dalai Lama inaugurated an interfaith "World Religions-Dialogue and Symphony" conference at Gujarat's Mahuva religions, according to Morari Bapu.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2010, the Dalai Lama, joined by a panel of scholars, launched the Common Ground Project, in Bloomington, Indiana (USA), which was planned by himself and Prince Ghazi bin Muhammad of Jordan during several years of personal conversations.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The project is based on the book *Common Ground between Islam and Buddhism*.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2019, the Dalai Lama fully sponsored the first-ever 'Celebrating Diversity in the Muslim World' conference in New Delhi on behalf of the Muslims of Ladakh.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's lifelong interest in science and technology dates from his childhood in Lhasa, Tibet, when he was fascinated by mechanical objects like clocks, watches, telescopes, film projectors, clockwork soldiers and motor cars, and loved to repair, disassemble and reassemble them.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Once, observing the Moon through a telescope as a child, he realised it was a crater-pocked lump of rock and not a heavenly body emitting its own light as Tibetan cosmologists had taught him.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has also said that had he not been brought up as a monk he would probably have been an engineer.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On his first trip to the west in 1973 he asked to visit Cambridge University's astrophysics department in the UK and he sought out renowned scientists such as Sir Karl Popper, David Bohm and Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, who taught him the basics of science.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama sees important common ground between science and Buddhism in having the same approach to challenge dogma on the basis of empirical evidence that comes from observation and analysis of phenomena.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Also in 1983, the American social entrepreneur and innovator R.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Adam Engle, who had become aware of the Dalai Lama's deep interest in science, was already considering the idea of facilitating for him a serious dialogue with a selection of appropriate scientists.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1984 Engle formally offered to the Dalai Lama's office to organise a week-long, formal dialogue for him with a suitable team of scientists, provided that the Dalai Lama would wish to fully participate in such a dialogue.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Within 48 hours the Dalai Lama confirmed to Engle that he was "truly interested in participating in something substantial about science" so Engle proceeded with launching the project.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Francisco Varela, having heard about Engle's proposal, then called him to tell him of his earlier discussions with the Dalai Lama and to offer his scientific collaboration to the project.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Engle accepted, and Varela assisted him to assemble his team of six specialist scientists for the first 'Mind and Life' dialogue on the cognitive sciences, which was eventually held with the Dalai Lama at his residence in Dharamsala in 1987.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This five-day event was so successful that at the end the Dalai Lama told Engle he would very much like to repeat it again in the future.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As Mind and Life Institute's remit expanded, Engle formalised the organisation as a non-profit foundation after the third dialogue, held in 1990, which initiated the undertaking of neurobiological research programmes in the United States under scientific conditions.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Sponsors and partners in these dialogues have included the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Johns Hopkins University, the Mayo Clinic, and Zurich University.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Apart from time spent teaching Buddhism and fulfilling responsibilities to his Tibetan followers, the Dalai Lama spends time and resources investigating the interface between Buddhism and science through the ongoing series of Mind and Life dialogues and its spin-offs.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As the institute's Cofounder and the Honorary chairman he has personally presided over and participated in all its dialogues, which continue to expand worldwide.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have given rise to dozens of DVD sets of the dialogues and books he has authored on them such as *Ethics for the New Millennium* and *The Universe in a Single Atom*, as well as scientific papers and university research programmes.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On the Tibetan and Buddhist side, science subjects have been added to the curriculum for Tibetan monastic educational institutions and scholarship.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] SEE learning focuses on developing critical thinking, ethical reasoning and compassion and stresses on commonalities rather than on the differences.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In particular, the Mind and Life Education Humanities & Social Sciences initiatives have been instrumental in developing the emerging field of Contemplative Science, by researching, for example, the effects of contemplative practice on the human brain, behaviour and biology.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have even had an impact in the Chinese capital.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2013 an 'academic dialogue' with a Chinese scientist, a Tibetan 'living Buddha' and a professor of Religion took place in Beijing.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Entitled "High-end dialogue: ancient Buddhism and modern science" it addressed the same considerations that interest the Dalai Lama, described as 'discussing about the similarities between Buddhism and modern science'.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama uses various meditation techniques, including analytic meditation and emptiness meditation.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2007, the 14th Dalai Lama said his reincarnation could be a woman.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This was mentioned again in 2015 and 2019.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In May 2011, the Dalai Lama retired from the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2011, the Dalai Lama repeated his statement in an interview with Canadian CTV News.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He added that Chinese laws banning the selection of successors based on reincarnation will not impact his decisions.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "Naturally my next life is entirely up to me.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And also this is not a political matter", he said in the interview.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama also added that he has not decided on whether he would reincarnate or be the last Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview with the German newspaper *Welt am Sonntag* published on 7 September 2014 the Dalai Lama stated "the institution of the Dalai Lama has served its purpose", and that "We had a Dalai Lama for almost five centuries.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The 14th Dalai Lama now is very popular.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Let us then finish with a popular Dalai Lama." In response, the Chinese government said the title of Dalai Lama has been conferred by the central government for hundreds of years and the 14th Dalai Lama has ulterior motives.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This was taken by Tibetan activists and *The Wire* to mean that China will make the Dalai Lama reincarnate no matter what.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Gyatso has also expressed fear that the Chinese government would manipulate any reincarnation selection in order to choose a successor that would go along with their political goals.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015, the 14th Dalai Lama has claimed he may be reincarnated as a mischievous blonde woman.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama said that if a female Dalai Lama comes, she should be more attractive.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Chinese politician Padma Choling accused the 14th Dalai Lama of flip-flopping with his various statements on the issue, and of hypocrisy as he himself was reincarnated.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also accused the 14th Dalai Lama of profaning Tibetan Buddhism "by doubting his reincarnation".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama stated that because of the feudal origin of the Dalai Lama reincarnation system, the reincarnation system should end.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, in July 2025, as the 14th Dalai Lama reached the age of 90, he addressed growing discussions about his succession by reaffirming that he will be reincarnated and that the process of identifying his successor should follow traditional Tibetan Buddhist practices.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a message shared during a prayer ceremony and posted on social media, the Dalai Lama stated that only his non-profit institution, Gaden Phodrang Foundation of the Dalai Lama, has the legitimate authority to oversee the selection of his reincarnation.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised that the identification of the 15th Dalai Lama should involve consultation with senior leaders of Tibetan Buddhist schools and with spiritual entities known as oath-bound Dharma Protectors, following established historical customs.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama reaffirmed that his reincarnation will occur outside China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a direct challenge to China, he asserted that the centuries-old spiritual institution bearing his name will endure beyond his death, emphasising that only his inner circle—not Beijing—will have the authority to identify his successor.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has stated that his successor will be born in a free country, suggesting that the next reincarnation could come from the Tibetan diaspora—around 140,000 people worldwide, with about half residing in India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In response, the Chinese government rejected the Dalai Lama's position.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Officials in Beijing stated that the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama, as well as other high-ranking Tibetan Buddhist figures such as the Panchen Lama, must be approved by the central government.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the government holds ultimate authority in confirming the identity of reincarnated Tibetan spiritual leaders.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Samdhong Rinpoche Lobsang Tenzin, a senior leader of the Dalai Lama's trust, affirmed the continuation of the Dalai Lama institution, stating that both a 15th and 16th Dalai Lama would follow.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said the current Dalai Lama would issue guidelines for identifying his successor.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Deputy speaker of the parliament of the Central Tibetan Administration Dolma Tsering Teykhang accused China of trying to control the reincarnation process and emphasised the need for the Dalai Lama to address the world directly.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his book, *Voice for the Voiceless*, published in 2025, the 14th Dalai Lama said Tibetans worldwide want the institution of the Dalai Lama to continue after his death and specified that his successor would be born in the "free world".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Despite initially advocating for Tibetan independence from 1961 to 1974, the Dalai Lama no longer supports it.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Instead he advocates for more meaningful autonomy for Tibetans within the People's Republic of China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This approach is known as the "Middle Way".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2005, the 14th Dalai Lama emphasised that Tibet is a part of China, and Tibetan culture and Buddhism are part of Chinese culture.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a speech at Kolkata in 2017, the Dalai Lama stated that Tibetans wanted to stay with China and they did not desire independence.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said that he believed that China after opening up, had changed 40 to 50 per cent of what it was earlier, and that Tibetans wanted to get more development from China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2020, the Dalai Lama stated that he did not support Tibetan independence and hoped to visit China as a Nobel Prize winner.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said "I prefer the concept of a 'republic' in the People's Republic of China.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama maintains close ties with India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2008, the Dalai Lama said that Arunachal Pradesh, partially claimed by China, is part of India, citing the disputed 1914 Simla Accord.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dhundup Gyalpo, the Dalai Lama's eventual secretary in New Delhi, argued that Tibetan and Chinese peoples have no connections apart from a few culinary dishes and that Chinese Buddhists could also be deemed "Indian in spirituality", because both Tibetan and Chinese Buddhism originated from India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has said that, from the perspective of the Buddhist precepts, abortion is an act of killing.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, he clarified a more nuanced position, stating, "... it depends on the circumstances.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If the unborn child will be retarded or if the birth will create serious problems for the parent, these are cases where there can be an exception.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed his opposition to the death penalty, saying that it contradicts the Buddhist philosophy of non-violence and that it expresses anger, not compassion.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] During a 2005 visit to Japan, a country which has the death penalty, the Dalai Lama called for the abolition of the death penalty and said in his address, "Criminals, people who commit crimes, usually society rejects these people.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Give them some form of punishment to say they were wrong, but show them they are part of society and can change.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Show them compassion." The Dalai Lama has also praised US states that have abolished the death penalty.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama says that he is active in spreading India's message of nonviolence and religious harmony throughout the world.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "I am the messenger of India's ancient thoughts the world over." He has said that democracy has deep roots in India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He says he considers India the master and Tibet its disciple, as great scholars went from India to Tibet to teach Buddhism.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has noted that millions of people lost their lives in violence and the economies of many countries were ruined due to conflicts in the 20th century.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has also critiqued proselytisation and certain types of conversion, believing the practices to be contrary to the fundamental ideas of religious harmony and spiritual practice.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has stated that "It's very important that our religious traditions live in harmony with one another and I don't think proselytizing contributes to this.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, the Dalai Lama attended the World Conference on Human Rights and made a speech titled "Human Rights and Universal Responsibility".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2001, in response to a question from a Seattle schoolgirl, the Dalai Lama said that it is permissible to shoot someone in self-defence (if the person was "trying to kill you") and he emphasised that the shot should not be fatal.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2013, the Dalai Lama criticised Buddhist monks' attacks on Muslims in Myanmar and rejected violence by Buddhists, saying: "Buddha always teaches us about forgiveness, tolerance, compassion.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If from one corner of your mind, some emotion makes you want to hit, or want to kill, then please remember Buddha's faith. ...
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] All problems must be solved through dialogue, through talk.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has consistently praised India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In December 2018, he said Muslim countries like Bangladesh, Pakistan and Syria should learn about religion from India for peace in the world.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked in 2019 about attacks on the minority community in India including a recent one against a Muslim family in Gurgaon, he said: "There are always a few mischievous people, but that does not mean it a symbol of that nation".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reiterated in December 2021 that he thought India was a role model for religious harmony in the world.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama advocates compassion for animals and frequently urges people to try vegetarianism or at least reduce their consumption of meat.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In Tibet, where historically meat was the most common food, most monks historically have been omnivores, including the Dalai Lamas.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Fourteenth Dalai Lama was raised in a meat-eating family but converted to vegetarianism after arriving in India, where vegetables are much more easily available and vegetarianism is widespread.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He spent many years as a vegetarian, but after contracting hepatitis in India and suffering from weakness, his doctors told him to return to eating meat which he now does twice a week.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This attracted public attention when, during a visit to the White House, he was offered a vegetarian menu but declined by replying, as he is known to do on occasion when dining in the company of non-vegetarians, "I'm a Tibetan monk, not a vegetarian".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His own home kitchen, however, is completely vegetarian.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, the English singer Paul McCartney wrote a letter to the Dalai Lama inquiring why he was not a vegetarian.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] As McCartney later told *The Guardian*, "He wrote back very kindly, saying, 'my doctors tell me that I must eat meat'.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And I wrote back again, saying, you know, I don't think that's right. [...] I think now he's vegetarian most of the time.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] I think he's now being told, the more he meets doctors from the west, that he can get his protein somewhere else. [...] It just doesn't seem right – the Dalai Lama, on the one hand, saying, 'Hey guys, don't harm sentient beings...
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has referred to himself as a Marxist and has articulated criticisms of capitalism.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reports hearing of communism when he was very young, but only in the context of the destruction of the Mongolian People's Republic.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] It was only when he went on his trip to Beijing that he learned about Marxist theory from his interpreter Baba Phuntsog Wangyal of the Tibetan Communist Party.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At that time, he reports, "I was so attracted to Marxism, I even expressed my wish to become a Communist Party member", citing his favourite concepts of self-sufficiency and equal distribution of wealth.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He does not believe that China implemented "true Marxist policy", and thinks the historical communist states such as the Soviet Union "were far more concerned with their narrow national interests than with the Workers' International".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Moreover, he believes one flaw of historically "Marxist regimes" is that they place too much emphasis on destroying the ruling class, and not enough on compassion.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He finds Marxism superior to capitalism, believing the latter is only concerned with "how to make profits", whereas the former has "moral ethics".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] On India–Pakistan relations, the Dalai Lama in October 2019 said: "There is a difference between Indian and Pakistani Prime Minister's speech at the UN.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Indian Prime Minister talks about peace, and you know what his Pakistan counterpart said, getting China's political support is Pakistan's compulsion.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Pakistani leaders should calm down and think beyond emotions and should follow a realistic approach".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama is outspoken in his concerns about environmental problems, frequently giving public talks on themes related to the environment.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has pointed out that many rivers in Asia originate in Tibet, and that the melting of Himalayan glaciers could affect the countries in which the rivers flow.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He acknowledged official Chinese laws against deforestation in Tibet, but lamented they can be ignored due to possible corruption.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He was quoted as saying "ecology should be part of our daily life"; personally, he takes showers instead of baths, and turns lights off when he leaves a room.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Around 2005, he started campaigning for wildlife conservation, including by issuing a religious ruling against wearing tiger and leopard skins as garments.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama supports the anti-whaling position in the whaling controversy, but has criticised the activities of groups such as the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society (which carries out acts of what it calls aggressive nonviolence against property).
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Before the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference, he urged national leaders to put aside domestic concerns and take collective action against climate change.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's stances on topics of sexuality have changed over time.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A monk since childhood, the Dalai Lama has said that sex offers fleeting satisfaction and leads to trouble later, while chastity offers a better life and "more independence, more freedom".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has said that problems arising from conjugal life sometimes even lead to suicide or murder.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has asserted that all religions have the same view about adultery.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also says that in modern times all common, consensual sexual practices that do not cause harm to others are ethically acceptable and that society should accept and respect people who are gay or transgender from a secular point of view.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his 1996 book *Beyond Dogma*, he described a traditional Buddhist definition of an appropriate sexual act as follows: "A sexual act is deemed proper when the couples use the organs intended for sexual intercourse and nothing else ...
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Homosexuality, whether it is between men or between women, is not improper in itself.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] What is improper is the use of organs already defined as inappropriate for sexual contact." He elaborated in 1997, conceding that the basis of that teaching was unknown to him.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also conveyed his own "willingness to consider the possibility that some of the teachings may be specific to a particular cultural and historic context".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, the Dalai Lama has expressed concern at "reports of violence and discrimination against" LGBT people and urged "respect, tolerance and the full recognition of human rights for all".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2014 interview with Larry King, the Dalai Lama expressed that same-sex marriage is a personal issue, can be ethically socially accepted, and that he personally accepts it.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also stated that if same-sex marriage is in contradiction with one's chosen traditions, then they should not follow it.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, on gender equality and sexism, the Dalai Lama proclaimed at the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, Tennessee: "I call myself a feminist.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Isn't that what you call someone who fights for women's rights?" He also said that by nature, women are more compassionate based on their biology and capacity for reproduction and maternal care.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He called on women to "lead and create a more compassionate world", citing the good works of nurses and mothers.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015 the Dalai Lama said in a BBC interview that if a female were to succeed him, "that female must be attractive, otherwise it is not much use." When asked if he was joking, he replied, "No.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] True!" The Dalai Lama followed with a joke about his success being due to his own appearance.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office later released a statement of apology citing the interaction as a translation error.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2020 statement in *Time* magazine on the COVID-19 pandemic, the Dalai Lama said that the pandemic must be combated with compassion, empirical science, prayer, and the courage of healthcare workers.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised "emotional disarmament" (seeing things with a clear and realistic perspective, without fear or rage) and wrote: "The outbreak of this terrible coronavirus has shown that what happens to one person can soon affect every other being.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In September 2018, speaking at a conference in Malmö, Sweden, the Dalai Lama said "I think Europe belongs to the Europeans", but also that Europe was "morally responsible" for helping "a refugee really facing danger against their life".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He stated that Europe has a responsibility to refugees to "receive them, help them, educate them", but that they should aim to return to their places of origin and that "they ultimately should rebuild their own country".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Speaking to German reporters in 2016, the Dalai Lama said there are "too many" refugees in Europe, adding that "Europe, for example Germany, cannot become an Arab country." He also said that "Germany is Germany".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dorje Shugden is an entity in Tibetan Buddhism that, since the 1930s, has become a point of contention over whether to include or exclude certain non-Gelug teachings.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1975 publication of the *Yellow Book* containing stories about Dorje Shugden acting wrathfully against Gelugpas who also practised Nyingma, the 14th Dalai Lama, himself a Gelugpa and advocate of an inclusive approach, publicly renounced the practice of Dorje Shugden.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Several groups broke away as a result, notably the New Kadampa Tradition (NKT).
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to Tibetologists, the Dalai Lama's disapproval has reduced the prevalence of Shugden sects among Tibetans in China and India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Shugden devotees have since complained about being ostracised when trying to get jobs or receive services.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's supporters expressed that any discrimination is neither systematic nor encouraged by him.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some Shugden movements such as the NKT have organised demonstrations as a form of protest.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some journalists have suggested that the Chinese government has taken advantage of the controversy.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office said that there was no ban or discrimination against Shugden worshippers.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 1998, the Dalai Lama's administration acknowledged that it received $1.7 million a year in the 1960s from the US government through a Central Intelligence Agency program.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked by CIA officer John Kenneth Knaus in 1995 to comment on the CIA Tibetan program, the Dalai Lama replied that though it helped the morale of those resisting the Chinese, "thousands of lives were lost in the resistance" and further, that "the U.S.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Government had involved itself in his country's affairs not to help Tibet but only as a Cold War tactic to challenge the Chinese." As part of the program the Dalai Lama received 180,000 dollars a year from 1959 till 1974 for his own personal use.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His administration's reception of CIA funding has become one of the grounds for some state-run Chinese newspapers to discredit him along with the Tibetan independence movement.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his autobiography *Freedom in Exile*, the Dalai Lama criticised the CIA again for supporting the Tibetan independence movement "not because they (the CIA) cared about Tibetan independence, but as part of their worldwide efforts to destabilize all communist governments".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama places highly in global surveys of the world's most admired men, ranking with Pope Francis as among the world's religious leaders cited as the most admired.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's appeal is variously ascribed to his charismatic personality, international fascination with Buddhism, his universalist values, and international sympathy for the Tibetans.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In the 1990s, many films were released by the American film industry about Tibet, including biopics of the Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This is attributed to both the Dalai Lama's 1989 Nobel Peace Prize as well as to the euphoria following the Fall of Communism.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The most notable films, *Kundun* and *Seven Years in Tibet* (both released in 1997), portrayed "an idyllic pre-1950 Tibet, with a smiling, soft-spoken Dalai Lama at the helm—a Dalai Lama sworn to non-violence": portrayals the Chinese government decried as ahistorical.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has his own pages on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has tried to mobilise international support for Tibetan activities.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has been successful in gaining Western support for himself and the cause of greater Tibetan autonomy, including vocal support from numerous Hollywood celebrities, most notably the actors Richard Gere and Steven Seagal, as well as lawmakers from several major countries.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Photos of the Dalai Lama were banned after March 1959 Lhasa protests until after the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1996 the Chinese Communist Party once again reinstated the total prohibition of any photo of the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Tibet Information Network, "authorities in Tibet have begun banning photographs of the exiled Dalai Lama in monasteries and public places, according to reports from a monitoring group and a Tibetan newspaper.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Plainclothes police went to hotels and restaurants in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, on 22 and 23 April and ordered Tibetans to remove pictures of the Dalai Lama ..." The ban continues in many locations throughout Tibet today.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In popular media, the Dalai Lama appeared on the HBO late-night talk show *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver* on 5 March 2017, where he discussed issues including Tibetan sovereignty, Tibetan self-immolations, and his succession plans.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A biographical graphic novel, *Man of Peace*, also envisaging the Dalai Lama's return to Tibet, was published by Tibet House US.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] *The Extraordinary Life of His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama: An Illuminated Journey,* illustrations and text by artist Rima Fujita, narrated by the Dalai Lama, was published by Simon and Schuster in 2021.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has received numerous awards and honours worldwide over his spiritual and political career.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] For a more complete list see Awards and honours presented to the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, the Norwegian Nobel Committee awarded him the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Committee officially gave the prize to the Dalai Lama for "the struggle of the liberation of Tibet and the efforts for a peaceful resolution" and "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, he became one of only six people ever to be granted Honorary Citizenship of Canada.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2007 he was named Presidential Distinguished Professor at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, the first time he accepted a university appointment.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He is the chief Patron of the Maha Bodhi Society of India, conferred upon him at the 2008 Annual General Meeting of the Maha Bodhi Society of India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At the 68th Annual Grammy Awards, he won the Grammy Award for Best Audio Book, Narration & Storytelling Recording.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a February 2023 video, the Dalai Lama was seen kissing a boy on the lips and asking the child to suck his tongue.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The incident took place at his temple in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, India.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Nearly 100 students were in attendance, as well as the boy's mother, a trustee of the event's organiser.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Her son had requested a hug from the Dalai Lama, who then asked for and received a kiss from the child, pulling him closer to touch lips.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After a pause, the Dalai Lama said "suck my tongue" and, with his tongue out, leaned toward the boy, who appeared nervous and withdrew after sticking out his own tongue.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview clip released by Voice of Tibet, the boy later said it had been a "good experience" meeting the Dalai Lama, from whom he received a lot of "positive energy".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The interaction was originally recorded by Voice of America, which posted the footage after editing out the "suck my tongue" part.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The removed portion of the clip resurfaced in April 2023, and the Dalai Lama's conduct received negative media coverage.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some victim groups and media commentators raised concerns of "child abuse", while the Tibetan Legal Association warned four Indian news outlets to retract parts of their reporting.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The office of His Holiness issued a statement saying that the Dalai Lama often teases "in an innocent and playful way", adding that he "wishes to apologize to the boy and his family ... for the hurt his words may have caused" and "regrets the incident".
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Penpa Tsering, the political leader of the Central Tibetan Administration, called the gesture an "innocent grandfatherly affectionate demeanour" followed by a "jovial prank" with a tongue.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He and other Tibetans accused "pro-Chinese sources" of being behind the video but have not provided any evidence.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some academics, Tibetan leaders and cultural groups described the situation as a cultural misunderstanding.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] They mentioned that sticking out one's tongue is a form of traditional Tibetan greeting to show respect or agreement, stemming from a tradition of performing the gesture to demonstrate that one is not reincarnated from the malevolent king Langdarma, who was said to have a black tongue.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The practice is not known to involve "sucking", however.
[src:nobel-prize/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The controversy also drew attention to past incidents where the Dalai Lama caressed the arm of a disabled girl sitting next to him and touched Lady Gaga's knee through her torn trousers before the star laughed.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] The **1961 Nobel Prize in Literature** was awarded to the Yugoslav writer Ivo Andrić (1892–1975) "for the epic force with which he has traced themes and depicted human destinies drawn from the history of his country." He is the first and only Serbian recipient of the literature prize.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Ivo Andrić began by writing poetry, and philosophers like Kierkegaard, Nietzsche, Kafka and Goethe had an impact on his philosophical views.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] But his preferred literary form would be the historical epic.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] The fates of people are illuminated against a historical, cultural, and religious backdrop in Andrić's writings, such as his monumental novel *Na Drini ćuprija* ("The Bridge on the Drina", 1945).
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] His stories show both immense love for individuals and brutality and violence.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] His writing is clear and full of information, and his stories are filled with insightful psychological observations.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] His other well-known literary oeuvres include *Travnička hronika* ("Travnika Chronicle", 1945) and *Prokleta avlija* ("The Damned Yard", 1954).
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Andrić earned ten nominations on four occasions.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] He was first nominated in 1958 by The Yugoslavian Author's Society.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] On 1961, he was recommended by four nominators from Elizabeth Hill, Lennart Breitholtz, Johannes Edfelt and the aforementioned society which led to his awarding.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] In total, the Swedish Academy's Nobel Committee received 93 nominations for 56 authors such as Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan, John Steinbeck (awarded in 1962), André Malraux, Graham Greene, Georges Simenon, Ramón Menéndez Pidal, Robert Frost and Rómulo Gallegos.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Fifteen of the nominees were nominated for the first time, among them Yasunari Kawabata (awarded in 1968), Gaston Bachelard, Cora Sandel, Jean Anouilh, Simone de Beauvoir, J.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] There were five female nominees namely Giulia Scappino Murena, Gertrud von le Fort, Karen Blixen, Cora Sandel and Simone de Beauvoir.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] The authors Jacques Stephen Alexis, Lucian Blaga, Joanna Cannan, Louis-Ferdinand Céline, Mazo de la Roche, Louis de Wohl, Hilda Doolittle, Frantz Fanon, Olga Forsh, Leonhard Frank, Simon Gantillon, Dashiell Hammett, Émile Henriot, George S.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Kaufman, Maurice Merleau-Ponty, Oliver Onions, Jessie Redmon Fauset, Mihail Sadoveanu, Peyami Safa, Frédéric-Louis Sauser (*known as* Blaise Cendrars), Clark Ashton Smith, Antanas Škėma, Dorothy Thompson and Maria Valtorta died in 1961 without having been nominated for the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] For the 1961 Nobel Prize in Literature, the Nobel committee of the Swedish Academy proposed Ivo Andrić, Graham Greene and the Danish author Karen Blixen, with Andrić receiving the majority of the votes.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Other contenders for the 1961 prize included the American poet Robert Frost and novelist E.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Forster, who were both passed over by the Nobel committee because of their advanced age.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Anders Österling said that Frost's age, 86, was "a fundamental obstacle, which the committee regretfully found it necessary to state".
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Other contenders such as Lawrence Durrell and the Italian novelist Alberto Moravia were ruled out for literary reasons, as were J.R.R.
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Tolkien whose prose Österling found "has not in any way measured up to storytelling of the highest quality".
[src:nobel-prize/1961-nobel-prize-in-literature] Andric donated the entire amount of the prize money, 250 232 Swedish crowns, to a fund for building a library in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Kissinger later tried to return the award, but the committee declined his offer.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The 1973 Nobel Peace Prize is often cited as one of, if not the most, controversial in the history of the award.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Two members of the Norwegian Nobel Committee resigned in protest, *The New York Times* referred to it as the "Nobel War Prize", and Tom Lehrer stated, "Political satire became obsolete when Henry Kissinger was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize".
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Henry Kissinger and Lê Đức Thọ had respectively been the United States and North Vietnamese representatives at discussions beginning in 1968 in Paris, France which aimed to put an end to the Vietnam War.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] On 26 October 1972, Kissinger held a press conference in Washington, D.C. in which he declared, "Peace is at hand." On 27 January 1973, the Paris Peace Accords were signed.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Under the agreement, direct American intervention in the conflict was ended and the remaining U.S. troops were to be withdrawn from Vietnam in exchange for a ceasefire and the cessation of conflict between North and South Vietnam.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] However, the agreement was not ratified by the United States Senate, and fighting restarted before American soldiers left the country.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Additionally, South Vietnam had not been consulted on the terms of the agreement, and in fact had not even been informed that negotiations had resumed.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The South Vietnamese government subsequently refused to accept the accords, and North and South Vietnamese forces both frequently broke the terms of the agreement.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] On 16 October 1973, the Norwegian Nobel Committee held a meeting at which it decided to give the 1973 Nobel Peace Prize to Kissinger and Thọ for their roles in negotiating the Paris Peace Accords.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The committee announced its decision later that day.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Thọ was the first Asian chosen for the award.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Two dissenting committee members, Einar Hovdhaugen and Helge Rognlien, resigned in protest of the decision.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] International responses were strongly polarized, especially regarding the decision to award Kissinger.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] At the time the award was given, fighting was still ongoing in Vietnam.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] In the United States, reactions were widely derisive.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] *The New York Times* published an editorial dubbing it the "Nobel War Prize", describing the award as "at the very least, premature".
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] In a joint letter to the Norwegian Parliament, multiple Harvard professors wrote that awarding Kissinger and Thọ was "more than a person with a normal sense of justice can take".
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] For only the second time in history, Norwegian Nobel Committee members resigned as a result of the decision; the first time being in 1935 in response to giving the award to Carl von Ossietzky.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Kissinger himself contemplated declining the prize, as he considered Thọ's nomination to be an affront.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] He is quoted as saying to Soviet ambassador Anatoly Dobrynin, "I figure it like Groucho Marx said, 'any club that took him in he would not want to join'.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The deadline for Thọ to accept of 1 October 1974 passed without Thọ accepting the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The award ceremony was held on 10 December 1973, on the traditional anniversary of Alfred Nobel's death, to give the Nobel Peace Prize to Kissinger.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Kissinger declined to attend, concerned that the event would be targeted by anti-war protestors.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] Kissinger received half of the allotted prize pool for 1973, roughly $65,000 (equivalent to $471,000 in 2025), which he used to set up a scholarship fund in the name of his parents for the children of dead or missing American servicemen.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] In total, the Norwegian Nobel Committee received 170 nominations for 45 nominees: 39 individuals and 8 organizations.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The following members of the Norwegian Nobel Committee were appointed by the Norwegian Parliament for 1973.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] As hostilities in Vietnam resumed in full, the 1975 spring offensive and subsequent fall of Saigon marked the complete failure of the Paris Peace Accords, and South Vietnam surrendered on 30 April 1975.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] As of February 2024, Lê Đức Thọ is the only person to have ever declined the Nobel Peace Prize, and one of only two people to ever decline any Nobel Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] The award has endured as a critique of the Nobel Prize and its chosen winners, and is often remembered as one of the most controversial Nobel prizes ever given.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] On 11 January 2023, documents from the 1973 nomination process were unsealed, showing that even the members of the committee who voted for Kissinger and Thọ believed that they could prove to be poor choices; further, they were skeptical that the Paris Accords would bring lasting peace.
[src:nobel-prize/1973-nobel-peace-prize] In an op-ed in the *National Review*, Jay Nordlinger argued that North Vietnam, not Kissinger, was responsible for the collapse of the Paris Peace Accords, and that an undue amount of backlash was directed at Kissinger as opposed to Thọ.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] José Saramago frequently makes use of allegory in his writing, and fanciful elements are interspersed with a detailed and critical look at society.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] A characteristic of Saramago's style is the blending of dialog and narration, in parabolic forms, with sparse punctuation and long sentences that can extend for several pages.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] In one of his most successful novels, *Ensaio sobre a Cegueira* ("Blindness", 1995), the population is stricken with an epidemic of blindness that quickly leads to societal collapse.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] Saramago's last published work was *Caim* ("Cain", 2009), which narrates Adam and Eve's son as he witnesses and recounts passages from the Bible that add to his increasing hatred of God.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] While Saramago had Portuguese citizenship, he was residing in Lanzarote, Spain, since 1991.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] José Saramago was a favourite to win the 1998 Nobel Prize in Literature along with his country-man and literary rival Antonio Lobo Antunes and Belgian writer Hugo Claus.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] The choice of Saramago as the Nobel Prize laureate was internationally generally well received.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] One commentator in the Swedish newspaper Dagens Nyheter described it as a safe choice: "an authorship that is appreciated by everyone and won't be questioned by anyone".
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] In Saramago's home country reactions were however radically mixed, lauded by the left wing press and heavily criticised by the bourgeois press.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] Following the Swedish Academy's decision to present Saramago with the Nobel Prize in Literature, the Vatican City questioned the decision on political grounds, though gave no comment on the aesthetic or literary components of his work.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] Saramago responded: "The Vatican is easily scandalized, especially by people from outside.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] They should just focus on their prayers and leave people in peace.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] I respect those who believe, but I have no respect for the institution." He received the news when he was about to fly to Germany for the Frankfurt Book Fair, and caught both him and his editor by surprise.
[src:nobel-prize/1998-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 2024, Saramago's widow Pilar del Rio and the José Saramago Foundation donated a number of Saramago's belongings to the Nobel Prize Museum in Stockholm, including a pair of his glasses, a stone found in Lanzarote that was important to him, and a manuscript written in his youth.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The **2009 Nobel Peace Prize** was awarded to United States president Barack Obama (b.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] 1961) for his "extraordinary efforts to strengthen international diplomacy and cooperation between peoples".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The Norwegian Nobel Committee announced the award on October 9, 2009, citing Obama's promotion of nuclear nonproliferation and a "new climate" in international relations fostered by Obama, especially in reaching out to the Muslim world.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The Nobel Committee's decision drew mixed reactions from US commentators and editorial writers across the political spectrum, as well as from the rest of the world.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama accepted the prize in Oslo on December 10, 2009.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama is the fourth president of the United States to have won the Nobel Peace Prize (after Theodore Roosevelt, Woodrow Wilson and Jimmy Carter, with Carter's honor happening after leaving office).
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The winner is selected by the Nobel Committee from nominations submitted by committee members and others.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Nominations for the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize closed just 11 days after Obama took office.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] There were 205 nominations for the 2009 award, which included Chinese and Afghan civil rights activists and African politicians.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Colombian senator Piedad Córdoba, Afghanistan's Sima Samar, Chinese dissident Hu Jia and Prime Minister of Zimbabwe Morgan Tsvangirai had been speculated to be favorites for the award.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The five members of the Nobel Committee are appointed by the Norwegian Parliament to roughly reflect the party makeup of that body.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The 2009 Committee comprised two members of the Norwegian Labour Party, one from the left-wing Socialist Left Party, one from the Conservative Party of Norway and one from the right-wing Progress Party.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The chairman of the committee was Thorbjørn Jagland, former Norwegian Labour Party prime minister and Secretary General of the Council of Europe since September 29, 2009.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The panel met six or seven times in 2009, beginning several weeks after the February 1 nomination deadline.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The winner was chosen unanimously on October 5, but was initially opposed by the Socialist Left, Conservative and Progress Party members until strongly persuaded by Jagland.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Jagland said "We have not given the prize for what may happen in the future.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] We are awarding Obama for what he has done in the past year.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] And we are hoping this may contribute a little bit for what he is trying to do," noting that he hoped the award would assist Obama's foreign policy efforts.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Jagland said the committee was influenced by a speech Obama gave about Islam in Cairo in June 2009, the president's efforts to prevent nuclear proliferation and climate change, and Obama's support for using established international bodies such as the United Nations to pursue foreign policy goals.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama was the fourth U.S. president to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, after Theodore Roosevelt (1906) and Woodrow Wilson (1919)—both of whom received the award during their terms—and Jimmy Carter (2002), who received the award 21 years after leaving office.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In addition, then-sitting vice president Charles Dawes was a co-winner with Austen Chamberlain (1925), and former vice president Al Gore was a co-winner with the U.N.'s Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (2007).
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama said he was "surprised" and "deeply humbled" by the award.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] "Throughout history, the Nobel Peace Prize has not just been used to honor specific achievement; it's also been used as a means to give momentum to a set of causes," Obama said.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama announced early that he would donate the full 10 million Swedish kronor (about US$1.4 million) monetary award to charity.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The largest donations were given to the housing charity Fisher House Foundation who received $250,000, and the Clinton Bush Haiti Fund which received $200,000.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama's winning of the peace prize was largely unanticipated and called a "stunning surprise" by *The New York Times*, though major oddsmaker Centrebet had in fact put him at 7–1 odds of winning, with Piedad Córdoba and Sima Samar at 6–1 and Morgan Tsvangirai at 7–1.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] There was widespread criticism of the Nobel Committee's decision from commentators and editorial writers across the political spectrum.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] *The New York Times* published a mildly supportive editorial which said the prize was "a (barely) implicit condemnation of Mr.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Bush created around the world is one of Mr.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama's great achievements in less than nine months in office.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama's willingness to respect and work with other nations is another." It said that much remains to be done.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Among those agreeing that the award was a criticism of the Bush administration were the editorial pages of the *Los Angeles Times*, *The Wall Street Journal*, and *The Washington Post*, as well as Thomas L.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Jonah Goldberg of the *National Review* said that "surely someone in Iran—or maybe the Iranian protestors generally—could have benefitted more from receiving the prize" while in *CounterPunch*, political journalist Alexander Cockburn said that, in historical context of other former U.S.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Presidents winning the Nobel Peace Prize, the award to Obama "represents a radical break in tradition, since he's only had slightly less than nine months to discharge his imperial duties".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Peter Beinart of the *Daily Beast* called the decision a "farce", while Noam Chomsky said: "In defense of the committee, we might say that the achievement of doing nothing to advance peace places Obama on a considerably higher moral plane than some of the earlier recipients".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Many were critical of the Nobel Committee.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] A *Wall Street Journal* editorial, noting Obama's comment that the world's problems "can't be met by any one leader or any one nation", opined, "What this suggests to us—and to the Norwegians—is the end of what has been called 'American exceptionalism'.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] This is the view that U.S. values have universal application and should be promoted without apology, and defended with military force when necessary.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] A *Los Angeles Times* editorial said the committee "didn't just embarrass Obama, it diminished the credibility of the prize itself".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Friedman of *The New York Times* wrote, "It dismays me that the most important prize in the world has been devalued in this way".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Much of the commentary across the political spectrum involved describing the award as something risible, with the humor focusing on Obama's getting the award without having accomplished much.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] According to an analysis in *The New York Times*, "it ... [is] striking how so many people seemed to greet the Nobel news with shock followed by laughter".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Other prominent commentators who often supported Obama but responded with ridicule included Peter Beinart and Ann Althouse.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] James Taranto wrote in *The Wall Street Journal* an article summarising various opinions on the Internet, concluding how the award was embarrassing for Obama.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] He said the award was a "staggeringly premature honor – the equivalent of a lifetime-achievement Oscar for a child star" and that it "makes yesterday's satire into today's news".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Fred Greenstein, presidential historian and author and professor of politics emeritus at Princeton University, told Fox News that giving President Obama the Nobel Peace Prize is a "premature canonization" and an "embarrassment to the Nobel process".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] *Slate* magazine blogger Mickey Kaus, *The New York Times* columnist David Brooks and former U.N. ambassador John Bolton amongst others, called for Obama to not accept the award; pundit Michael Crowley argued that it was a "mixed blessing".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Subsequent to the award many Americans now consider that Obama did not deserve it in the light of following events.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Opponents of the award cite the expansion of the war on terror and the large increase in the number of drone strikes carried out under Obama, specifically in Pakistan.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] There have been a number of calls for Obama to either return the award or to have the Nobel Committee recall it, most recently in 2013.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In April 2013 a petition was begun asking the Nobel Committee to rescind the Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The petition garnered 10,000 signatures in its first day and nearly 20,000 by the end of its first week.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Nobel laureate and former U.S. vice president Al Gore called the award "extremely well deserved".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama received congratulations and kind words from other elected officials, such as from House speaker Nancy Pelosi and former rival, Senator John McCain, who said, "As Americans, we're proud when our president receives an award of that prestigious category".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In 2015, Geir Lundestad, the non-voting Director of the Nobel Institute and secretary for the Nobel Committee at the time of the award, published a memoir, *Secretary of Peace*.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In it, he wrote "In hindsight, we could say that the argument of giving Obama a helping hand was only partially correct.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Many of Obama's supporters believed it was a mistake." Lundestad said that Obama had been surprised by the award, and considered not going to Oslo to accept it.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] He also said in his memoir that Obama had since failed to live up to the Nobel Committee's expectations.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] A poll conducted by Synovate for the newspaper *Dagbladet* showed that 43% of the Norwegian population believed giving Obama the prize was right, while 38% believed it was wrong.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The poll showed a sharp divide between younger and older people; of those over 60 years of age 58% were for and only 31% against it.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Of those between 18 and 29 years of age, only 25% approved of the decision, while 42% disapproved.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The award divided opinion among politicians.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg congratulated Obama for a "well-deserved prize".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Siv Jensen, leader of the opposition Progress Party, said that while Obama had taken several good initiatives the committee should have waited to see their results.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Erna Solberg, leader of the Conservative Party, also said that the prize came early and increased pressure on Obama to live up to the expectation.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Torstein Dahle, the leader of the far leftist party Red, called the award a scandal, citing the fact that Obama was the commander-in-chief of a country at war in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The response from U.S. allies was generally positive; reactions around the world were mixed or negative.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Several Nobel Laureates commented: Bangladeshi economist Muhammad Yunus (co-winner 2006 prize) said the committee's award was "an endorsement of [Obama] and the direction he is taking".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Archbishop Desmond Tutu said the award to Obama "anticipates an even greater contribution towards making our world a safer place for all".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] "He has not yet made a real input." The 14th Dalai Lama congratulated Obama.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon praised the Nobel Committee's choice.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] "We are entering an era of renewed multilateralism ...
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In Europe, French President Nicolas Sarkozy said the award would reinforce Obama's determination to work for justice and peace.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] He added that the award "finally confirms the return of America in the hearts of all the peoples of the world".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Dmitry Medvedev, then-president of Russia, said the award would encourage warmer U.S.–Russian relations, and he hoped it would "serve as an additional incentive" for both governments to foster a better "climate in world politics".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] British Prime Minister Gordon Brown sent a private message of congratulations to President Obama.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Hope that the prize would assist Obama's efforts toward nuclear disarmament was also a part of congratulatory statements from Ireland's Taoiseach Brian Cowen and German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Federico Lombardi said the Vatican "appreciated" the nomination.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In Australia, former Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said that the selection was "a political decision of gross stupidity", laying the blame on the selection committee for a "hideous display of cynical politics".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Stuart Rees, director of the Sydney Peace Foundation in Australia, questioned the award.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] "Perhaps the Nobel organisation wants to give him a magic wand.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In Asia and the Middle East: Afghanistan's president Hamid Karzai said that Obama was the "appropriate" person to win the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Siamak Hirai, a spokesman for Karzai, said, "His hard work and his new vision on global relations, his will and efforts for creating friendly and good relations at global level and global peace make him the appropriate recipient of the Nobel Peace Prize".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Taliban spokesman Zabiullah Mujahid said the decision was ridiculous, saying, "The Nobel prize for peace?
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Indonesia's Masdar Mas'udi, deputy head of the Islamic organisation Nahdlatul Ulama, praised Obama's policy towards his country as confirmation of his worthiness as a Nobel laureate.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] "I think it's appropriate because he is the only American president who has reached out to us in peace," he said.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In Latin America, former Cuban president Fidel Castro called the award "positive" and said the prize should be seen as a criticism to the "genocidal policy" carried out by past U.S. presidents.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Venezuelan foreign minister Nicolás Maduro said the award was a surprise and perhaps premature.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In Africa, the news of the Obama Nobel Peace Prize was positively received.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Kenyan president Mwai Kibaki issued a statement saying that the prize was a "recognition of the contribution [Obama is] making for the well being of humanity".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In 2011, Bolivian president Evo Morales and Russian Liberal Democratic Party leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky condemned the award, calling it hypocritical in light of US policy during the Libyan Civil War.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] President Obama accepted the Nobel Peace prize in person at the Oslo City Hall in Norway on December 10, 2009.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In a 36-minute speech, reportedly written by Obama and then edited by Jon Favreau and Ben Rhodes, he discussed the tensions between war and peace and the idea of a "just war".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The address contained elements of the ideas of Reinhold Niebuhr, someone Obama once described as one of his favorite philosophers.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The speech was generally well received by American pundits on both ends of the political spectrum.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Several noted similarities between Obama's message and the rhetoric of President George W.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] This was also mentioned by former Bush speechwriter Michael Gerson, who called it a "very American speech" and wrote that "Obama was recognizing that the great commitments and themes of American foreign policy are durably bipartisan".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] A number of prominent Republican politicians publicly praised the speech, including Newt Gingrich and Sarah Palin.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Conservative *The New York Times* columnist Ross Douthat called it an oftentimes impressive speech that was "An extended defense of using realist means in the service of liberal internationalist ends".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Columnist Andrew Sullivan distinguished between the Obama and Bush messages, stating that "Obama is *far more conservative* than his predecessor" in his views on human imperfection, reality, and war; he also linked the speech back to the tragic nature of Obama's line "the audacity of hope".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Former Jimmy Carter speechwriter Hendrik Hertzberg said that the speech "will live on for a long time as a text for peacemakers in power".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Abroad, British historian Simon Schama said of the speech that "in its seriousness, bravery and clarity, [it] was on a par with FDR and Churchill" and "summoned the spirit of Cicero".
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] President Obama reduced the number of United States Army soldiers fighting in Afghanistan and Iraq, but expanded the use of unmanned air-strikes on these countries, as well as Pakistan, Yemen, Syria, Libya and Somalia.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] In 2016, President Obama joked in an interview with Stephen Colbert that even he didn't know why he had received the award.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Analysis by the Council on Foreign Relations suggests that the United States Army dropped 79 per cent of all 30,743 coalition bombs in 2016.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] Obama has been at war for longer than any other president in US history.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] The secretary of the Norwegian Nobel Committee, Geir Lundestad, said in 2015 that awarding the prize to Obama failed to achieve what the committee hoped it would.
[src:nobel-prize/2009-nobel-peace-prize] "Even many of Obama's supporters believed that the prize was a mistake," he says.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The **2010 Nobel Peace Prize** was awarded to imprisoned Chinese human rights activist Liu Xiaobo (1955–2017) "for his long and non-violent struggle for fundamental human rights in China".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu, who was backed by former Czech president Václav Havel and anti-apartheid activist and cleric Desmond Tutu, also a Nobel Peace Prize winner, received the award among a record field of more than 200 nominees.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The decision, while widely praised by foreign intellectuals and politicians, was quickly condemned by the Chinese government and the state media.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] A number of countries, including Saudi Arabia and Russia, also denounced the award and what they regarded as interference in China's domestic affairs.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Following the announcement, official censorship was applied within China—on the Internet, television and in print media.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The government strongly denounced the award and summoned the Norwegian ambassador in Beijing to make a formal protest.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Chinese authorities arrested citizens who attempted to celebrate.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu's wife was put under house arrest before the decision of the Nobel Committee was announced.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Chinese diplomats moved to pressure other countries not to attend the award ceremony, which was scheduled for 10 December.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The diplomatic missions of democratic countries in Oslo received warning letters from their Chinese counterparts; the deputy foreign minister also warned countries of "the consequences".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In December, the Chinese Foreign Ministry continued the rhetorical assault, stating "more than 100 countries and international organisations [had] expressed explicit support of China's position".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In the end, 46 countries attended of the 65 invited (the People's Republic of China and 19 other nations declined invitations).
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu was the first person of Chinese nationality to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize and the first to be awarded a Nobel Prize of any kind while residing in China.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu was the third person to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize while in prison or detention after Germany's Carl von Ossietzky (1935) and Burma's Aung San Suu Kyi (1991).
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] As the laureate was absent, Liu's place on the podium was unoccupied; Norwegian actress Liv Ullmann read *I Have No Enemies*, an essay that Liu had written for his trial in December 2009, in place of the acceptance speech.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Nobel Committee disclosed there were a record number of nominations in 2010—a total of 237, of which 38 were organisations.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Although the committee has a policy of keeping nominations confidential for 50 years, some nominators made announcements.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Among the nominees were Russian human rights activist Svetlana Gannushkina, the International Space Station, the Internet and its three founders Larry Roberts, Vint Cerf and Tim Berners-Lee.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Also on the list were Chinese dissidents Liu Xiaobo, Hu Jia, Gao Zhisheng, Chen Guangcheng, Bao Tong, and Rebiya Kadeer.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu was nominated by International PEN, the worldwide association of writers.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] His challenging ideas caught the attention of the intellectuals; he lectured all over China and abroad.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] He was in New York when the 1989 pro-democracy movement erupted in China; he returned immediately to China and spent most of his time amongst the protesters in Tiananmen Square.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] This, and his subsequent leadership role in the *Charter 08* pro-democracy manifesto for China, led the Chinese authorities to censor his views as subversive.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu was jailed for 11 years on 25 December 2009, for "inciting subversion of state power".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman said "It would be completely wrong for the Nobel Prize committee to award the prize to [Liu]".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In January 2010, Václav Havel and others—including the 14th Dalai Lama, André Glucksmann, Vartan Gregorian, New Zealand politician Mike Moore, Karel Schwarzenberg, Desmond Tutu and Grigory Yavlinsky—published an article endorsing Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] On 7 October 2010, Norwegian television networks reported that Liu Xiaobo was the front-running candidate for the Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Irish bookmaker Paddy Power paid out two days before the announcement following an increase in bets.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Shortly before the announcement, Liu's wife, Liu Xia, declined telephone interviews, saying the police were at her home.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Her telephone went unanswered once the announcement was made.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Nobel Committee chairman Thorbjørn Jagland made the announcement on 8 October 2010 in Oslo, mentioning that the choice of Liu had become clear early in the process.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The monetary component of the prize would be 10 million Swedish kronor (US$1.5 million).
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] At 2 pm on the day of announcement, a crowd of about 100 journalists, supporters, and friends who had gathered outside the main entrance to the Beijing housing estate where the Lius resided were denied entry.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The *South China Morning Post* reported that policemen stationed inside their apartment at the time of the announcement prevented Liu Xia from meeting with journalists and other well-wishers.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] It was not immediately clear whether Liu Xiaobo was aware of the award.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] By that time, Liu Xia said she had been told she would be taken to Liaoning to see her husband in prison.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Meetings and gatherings to celebrate in several cities were prevented or abruptly broken up by police; one such celebration dinner in Beijing, attended by 20 people, was broken up by police, and the attendees were detained.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Chinese media avoided the story of Liu's Peace Prize, in marked contrast with their previous announcements of other recipients of Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The official Xinhua News Agency downplayed all but the literature prize, and most other mainland news portals followed the Xinhua lead; popular internet portals such as Sina.com and NetEase deleted pages dedicated to stories related to all five Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] At 6 pm, the source said that although the official news release had been issued, all media were ordered by the Central Propaganda Department not to publish it.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Major domestic newspapers in China had coverage on their inner pages.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] *Guangming Daily*, *Economic Daily*, *Beijing Daily*, *The Beijing News*, and Shanghai's *Wen Hui Bao* published the Xinhua-sanctioned report the following day.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] China Central Television's main evening news programme, *Xinwen Lianbo*, did not report on it.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Chinese journalists and dissidents said the Central Propaganda Department had instructed media to censor or otherwise under-report on Liu Xiaobo and the peace prize award.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Foreign broadcast coverage, such as from the BBC and CNN, was blacked out whenever Liu was mentioned.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In Guangdong, signal carriers for Hong Kong TVB were interrupted for approximately eight minutes during the 6 pm evening news programme, blocking the news item for the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Xinhua argued on 17 October that the Communist Party had made "unremitting efforts to promote and safeguard human rights", and questioned how Liu's actions had contributed to human rights progress for the Chinese people.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The journal employed the traditional hard-liner phrase "people with ulterior motives" (别有用心的人)—directed to at least one student.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] It further denounced the "farcical" Nobel decision to use the award as "a tool ... in their relentless effort to undermine China and frustrate its development".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The *Beijing Daily* published an editorial on the day of the award ceremony entitled "Why not give the peace prize to Julian Assange?".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Following the announcement on 8 October 2010, Xinhua relayed the Russian state-owned news agency's denunciation of the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] China protested to Norway, saying that China–Norway relations had been damaged.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Elsewhere, performances of a Norwegian musical starring Alexander Rybak scheduled for the following month also fell victim to the diplomatic fallout, according to the composer.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In early December, Norway said its bilateral trade talks with China had been delayed indefinitely.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In the days immediately preceding the award ceremony, foreign media reported that Liu's home was under tight security.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] By what a correspondent for *The Guardian* called "a peculiar coincidence", construction barriers were erected on both sides of the road at the southern entrance of the residential complex which obscured the estate.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Police cars were positioned on every nearby street corner; uniformed and plain-clothes police officers patrolled outside the apartment block, and a radio surveillance vehicle was stationed at the entrance to the compound.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Neighbouring businesses were affected: the owner of a nearby restaurant was quoted as saying government officials had told him to close the business temporarily.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu Xia was under house-arrest almost immediately after the announcement, and was escorted to Liaoning to visit her imprisoned husband.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] She reported that she was denied visitors, her telephones were repeatedly down, and complained that even her elderly mother had not been able to get through to her.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Visitors were denied entrance to her residential compound, including Norwegian diplomats who had tried to visit her on 12 October; she was able to send out a few messages through Twitter.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Chinese police stationed there cordoned off the area.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Thus, journalists and well-wishers were kept at bay for several hours after the announcement; as she was being taken away to see her husband, Reuters heard her say "they are forcing me to leave Beijing".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Dissident groups reported on 18 October that numerous supporters and associates of Liu may have been detained by police—that Tiananmen Mother Ding Zilin, and her husband Jiang Peikun, had not been seen or heard of for four days, and that their phones were cut off.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Writer Jiang Qisheng went missing just days after the Nobel announcement.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] As exiled prominent activists and former activists were reportedly preparing to attend the award ceremony, some prominent individuals and activists inside China experienced travel problems.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Economist Mao Yushi (who had signed *Charter 08*), Ai Weiwei, and the human-rights lawyer Liu Xiaoyuan were all barred from outbound travel at Beijing's airport, ostensibly because their departure from China could "endanger state security".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu's lawyer, Mo Shaoping, and Peking University law professor He Weifang were stopped from boarding their flight to London in November.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The *South China Morning Post* reported that even the spouses and children of some outspoken intellectuals experienced outbound travel restrictions.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Ai speculated that the refusal to let him board a flight for Korea may have been directly connected with the following week's prize-giving ceremony.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu Xia expressed her gratitude to the Nobel Committee, Liu's proposers, and those who have been supporting him since 1989, including the Tiananmen Mothers—family members or representatives of those who were killed, or had disappeared, in the military crackdown of the protests of 4 June 1989.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] She said, "The prize should belong to all who signed *Charter 08* and were jailed due to their support".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu Xia informed the laureate of his award during a visit to Jinzhou Prison on 9 October 2010, one day after the official announcement.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] She reported that Liu wept and dedicated the award to those who suffered as a result of the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989, saying: "The award is first and foremost for the Tiananmen martyrs" After Ms.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu returned home, she was put under house arrest and was watched by armed guards.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] She expressed the desire to attend the prize-giving in Norway in December, but was sceptical of her chances of being allowed to do so.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu Xia wrote an open letter to 143 prominent figures, encouraging them to attend the award ceremony in Oslo.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] John Pomfret of *The Washington Post* said a wide spectrum of Chinese and foreigners believed that Liu's award "could actually resonate more deeply within China than any similar act in years".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Artist and critic Ai Weiwei said that, although the regime ought to feel the most ashamed, "intellectuals who had drifted away from their public responsibilities" should bear some of that burden for betraying values they once strove for.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Ai said that the Prize was a message from the international community to the Chinese government to respect universal human values, notwithstanding China's economic performance.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Writer Liao Yiwu, a close friend of Liu, described it as "a big moment in Chinese history".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Another writer, Yu Jie, said he spent the night awake with tears streaming down his face – "Twenty years ago Liu Xiaobo said that China needed someone with moral clarity about what China needs.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Now he has become just that person, that he himself was looking for", he said.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Exiled 1989 student leader Wang Dan said he was "ecstatic".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] *The Globe and Mail* said that while many activists agreed he was worthy of the award, some radical reformers within Chinese democracy movement, such as Wei Jingsheng, see the moderate Liu as the wrong choice due to his advocacy of a gradual path to constitutional democracy in China.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Renmin University professor Zhang Ming felt the award would not have much direct impact.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] However, economist Mao Yushi believed that there were many factors affecting political reform in China.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] He stated that the prize was an impetus from the international community for the process of reform that was already under way, and that the impact of the award to Liu would be felt by the current generation of leaders, and beyond.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu was once an eminent scholar, but was reportedly little-known inside the People's Republic of China (PRC) at the time of the award due to official censorship.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Those who had heard about Liu had mixed views about him.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Some clearly supported the government position, whereas one university student was quoted as saying "George Orwell probably had no idea that what he wrote would end up being the reality of China now." "Liu Xiaobo" and "Nobel Peace Prize" became the most searched terms among internet users in China.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] However, some time after the release of the official response from the Chinese Foreign Ministry, government censors screened the news item, and there were reports of searches in China using Chinese search engines returning error pages.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Web searches using Chinese search engines for "Liu Xiaobo" in Chinese without attaching the words "Peace Prize", gave information about Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Yet most sites found "Liu" plus "Peace Prize" yield only the official foreign ministry response.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] CNN reported that any mention of "Nobel Prize" on microblogging sites was censored.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] One person claimed that his SIM card was deactivated after he sent a text message to a relative about the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Accustomed to circumventing Chinese internet censorship, bloggers and forum-users used variants of Liu's name and posted subtle or cryptic messages to express their elation about the award or sarcasm towards the state.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The statement on 8 October by blogger Han Han consisted of only a pair of double quote marks.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Less than three weeks after the announcement of the award to Liu, the Nobel Peace Prize website came under a cyber attack.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] There was an attempt to hack into the computer of the secretary of the Nobel Committee, Geir Lundestad by a forged email on 3 November.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] A number of individuals received an email containing a trojan horse purportedly disguised as a pdf-file invitation to the award ceremony from the Oslo Freedom Forum.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Investigators traced both the attack and the email to an intermediate server reportedly in a Taiwanese university.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Experts say the address had been falsified, and the exact origin was unknown; it was emphasised that no link to any party in mainland China could be established.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] After activists posted photographs of a symbolic empty chair on Internet fora and noticeboards, censors responded by removing the images and making "empty chair" a banned search term.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Many political groups—including the Democratic Party and the Hong Kong Journalists Association—welcomed the decision and congratulated Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Journalists Association expressed their gratitude and encouragement for Liu's award, and their hope for the early unconditional release of Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Hong Kong's Chief Executive, Donald Tsang, and government ministers Leung Chun-ying, and Gregory So, all declined to comment to the press.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The award will be seen in many quarters as acknowledging their sacrifice for the values it upholds." Hong Kong-based Phoenix Television, which transmits throughout mainland China by satellite, limited its report to the foreign ministry's statement denouncing the honour.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] About twenty activists held a celebration in front of the central government liaison office.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Their celebration was broken up and the activists were arrested for assault after a guard was accidentally sprayed with champagne.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] A human rights monitor, and a Democratic Party legislator, denounced the "absurd" reaction of the police.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Speaker of Hong Kong's legislature turned down an adjournment motion on 15 October submitted by Leung Kwok-hung that called for the release of Liu on grounds that such debate "lacked urgency and would not produce irreversible consequences".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] A candlelight ceremony was held in the city's central business district to coincide with the award ceremony; organisers said 1,000 people attended.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Chinese-language press reported on rumours that Chinese officials had approached high-level executives at TVB and CableTV, asking them not to broadcast the ceremony live on their channels; executives affirmed their plans to broadcast—scheduling for the event was immutable.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] TVB News and now TV executives categorically denied having been contacted by Chinese authorities to pull the plug on coverage.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] An editorial in the *South China Morning Post* said: "this heavy-handed reaction [to Liu's award] is counterproductive to [China's] image and the respect it wants as a peaceful superpower.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Liu's award did pose a dilemma, but having made its point at the outset Beijing had little further to gain.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The *Taipei Times* said the award suggested strong support for China's democracy movement, and predicted the inevitability of change.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] "The CCP needs to decide whether to attempt to obstruct democracy or facilitate its development.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] If it chooses the former then history will pass it by, just as it did the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] If, however, the CCP decides to embrace change then it could ... remain a political force" like the Kuomintang in Taiwan.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] This official position was reiterated to the People's Republic of China by their Norwegian ambassador.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Norwegian newspaper *Aftenposten* revealed that Foreign Minister Støre had a pre-emptive meeting with Nobel Committee chairman Thorbjørn Jagland, about Liu as the expected recipient, two weeks before the announcement.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] According to anonymous sources within both the Foreign Ministry and the Nobel Committee itself, Støre is said to have raised certain "concerns".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Norwegian press quoted Jagland as saying that this enquiry was of such a peculiar kind that he would have to present the Nobel Committee with the minutes of the meeting.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Former Nobel Committee chairman Ole Danbolt Mjøs and a number of Norwegian researchers and politicians criticised Støre for breaching protocol and meddling in the work of the committee.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Norwegian peace activist and author, Fredrik S.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Heffermehl criticised the Nobel Committee for failing to follow Alfred Nobel's dying wish to promote disarmament, by giving the award to Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Heffermehl said that less than 50 percent of the awards made after World War II had been made in accordance with Nobel's will.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Leading politicians in the Western world welcomed the news and called for the release of Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The European Union and member governments praised the decision, and also called on China to release Liu.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Japan greeted the award and emphasised the need for respect of human rights, but did not call for Liu's release; Premier Naoto Kan told a parliamentary committee Liu's release was "desirable".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Australian prime minister, Julia Gillard, said Australia was strongly against Liu's imprisonment, and "welcome[d] the fact that his work has been recognised internationally now with the Nobel Peace Prize", while the Australian Greens leader Bob Brown described the decision as "inspiring".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Brown contrasted Norway's courage with the "sheer ignorance and gutlessness of most of Australia's politicians on the plight of campaigning democrats in China".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] President of the United States Barack Obama lauded Liu's eloquence and courage, while his government called for his immediate release.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Non-aligned and developing countries such as Russia, Brazil and India, many Asian and Middle Eastern countries were silent.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Cuban and Venezuelan governments were notably critical.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez sided with China, saying the award should be given to those who "have done the most for fraternity between nations, the abolition or reduction of standing armies and promotion of peace congresses".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Dalai Lama expressed confidence that China would one day enjoy responsible governance through the efforts of Liu and others calling for democracy and freedom.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] However, Andre Geim and Konstantin Novoselov, who were awarded the 2010 Nobel Prize in Physics, attacked the Nobel committee as "retired Norwegian politicians who have spent all their careers in a safe environment, in an oil-rich modern country.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] They try to extend their views of the world, how the world should work and how democracy works in another country." They also felt that China should be given due credit for undisputed improvements in human rights and the economy over the last 10 years.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Novoselov questioned: "What is a dictatorship?
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Human Rights Watch said the 2010 award honours "all those in China who struggle daily to make the government more accountable" and "shatter[s] the myth where the Communist Party presents itself as the voice of the Chinese people".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Secretary General of Amnesty International, said: "the Chinese government might see this is as a victory, but they would be mistaken ...
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] He also argued that the choice of Liu was divisive in view of China's memory of Western imperialism, and of Alfred Nobel's dying wish to reward a person "who shall have done the most or the best work for fraternity between nations".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Professor Sidney Rittenberg said: "One does not have to approve of Mr Liu's imprisonment in order to disapprove of his choice as a Nobel laureate ...
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] State-owned Russian news agency RIA Novosti immediately criticised the prize as a "political tool"—a denunciation swiftly picked up and relayed by Xinhua.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Radio Free Europe reported Solidarnost (in Russia) planned to hold a public rally in support of Liu in Saint Petersburg, but the authorities refused permission.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In the end, 10 activists staged a protest outside the Chinese consulate there.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] In an editorial, *The Guardian* said "to many western ears, the clamour of China's markets is louder than the pleas of its dissidents.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The Nobel committee is one of few institutions with sufficient status to be heard around the world.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] News agencies reported the Confucius Peace Prize, established at the suggestion of *Global Times* in response to the award of the Nobel Peace Prize to a jailed dissident.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] The organiser denied any involvement of the Chinese government in the award and the Minister of Culture said they only became aware of the prize due to the press coverage.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] Hong Kong's *Ming Pao*, which had obtained a copy of the letter from the organisers of the Confucius award to the 'winner', suggested that this was indeed unofficial—the letter did not bear the Ministry of Culture's official seal.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] *Die Welt* said the rival award was "stupid".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p01] 4 December 2012, 134 Nobel Prize laureates wrote to new General Secretary of Communist Party Xi Jinping, calling for the immediate release of Liu Xiaobo and the lifting of the house arrest of his wife Liu Xia.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] At least two European embassies in Norway were sent letters by their Chinese counterparts, denouncing the prize for being an interference in China's internal affairs and reaffirming their stance that Liu had committed crimes in China.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] One diplomat said his embassy's letter from the Chinese embassy requested obliquely that they "refrain from attending any activity directed against China." The Norwegian Nobel Committee said its invitation to the Chinese ambassador to attend the prize-giving was returned unanswered.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The Chinese Vice Foreign Minister also warned countries supporting Liu's award that they would have to "take responsibility for the consequences".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] In December, the Chinese foreign ministry continued to denounce the award as "interference by a few clowns".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] On the eve of the award ceremony, China continued the rhetoric against the Nobel Committee and the West.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] A spokesman said: "We hope that those countries who have received invitations can tell right from wrong and uphold justice.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Colombia, Serbia, the Philippines and Ukraine initially announced they would not attend the ceremony, but later accepted the invitation.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The award ceremony, held as planned in Oslo City Hall on the afternoon of 10 December, was attended by about 1,000 VIPs, diplomats and guests.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Representing Norway were King Harald V, Queen Sonja and a number of politicians and officials; among the 48 foreign dignitaries was the US House Speaker, Nancy Pelosi.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Outside the hall, pro-democracy and human rights activists demonstrated; about 50 China supporters held a protest outside the Norwegian Parliament.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The hall was decked with an immense portrait of Liu for the event.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] During the ceremony, the Nobel committee chairman Thorbjørn Jagland credited China's leaders with the "extraordinary" economic transformation that has lifted millions of people out of poverty, but said they "must regard criticism as positive" considering the nation's new status as a world power.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Liu's award marks the third occasion that the Prize has been bestowed upon a person in prison or detention, after Carl von Ossietzky (1935) and Aung San Suu Kyi (1991); Liu and Ossietzky were the only ones not to be present or represented by close family at the awards ceremony.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The Nobel diploma and the prize were symbolically placed by Jagland on an empty chair meant for the absent laureate.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Norwegian actress Liv Ullmann read *I Have No Enemies*, an essay by Liu written for his trial in December 2009.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The proceedings were televised by the international media, but broadcast signals of CNN and BBC inside China were reportedly blocked.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Images of and references to 'empty chair' also became the target of official censorship.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Following the ceremony, an evening rally of more than 1,000 people in Oslo called for Liu's release.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The marchers headed for the Grand Hotel, where laureates traditionally greet the crowd from the balcony.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Assembled Chinese activists and dissidents said they were inspired by the award, that it was a much-needed morale-booster, and expressed hope that it would be a catalyst to resurrect the moribund Chinese pro-democracy movement.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] On the other hand, a huge image with three empty chairs and five cranes adorned the front page the edition of 12 December of the *Southern Metropolis Daily*; ambiguously, the headline read: "2010 Asian Para Games Are Ready to Start Tonight in Guangzhou".
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] *China Digital Times* offered the interpretation that 'crane' in Chinese (*he*) is a homonym for 'congratulations' and the first character of 'peace'.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The Nobel Peace Prize Concert to commemorate the 2010 prize was held on 11 December, the night following the award ceremony, as is the tradition.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] It was hosted by Denzel Washington and Anne Hathaway.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] The roster of confirmed performers announced before the award included Herbie Hancock, Florence and the Machine, Colbie Caillat, Elvis Costello.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Those who were confirmed later included Barry Manilow, Jamiroquai, A.
[src:nobel-prize/2010-nobel-peace-prize-p02] Rahman, India.Arie, Robyn and Sivert Høyem.
[src:nobel-prize/2020-nobel-prizes] The **2020 Nobel Prizes** were awarded by the Nobel Foundation, based in Sweden.
[src:nobel-prize/2020-nobel-prizes] Six categories were awarded: Physics, Chemistry, Physiology or Medicine, Literature, Peace, and Economic Sciences.
[src:nobel-prize/2020-nobel-prizes] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, programming for Nobel Week was limited, with some ceremonies and events taking place virtually.
[src:nobel-prize/2020-nobel-prizes] The Chemistry Prize's awarding to Charpentier and Doudna provoked debates about who "discovered" CRISPR, with some arguing that scientists like Feng Zhang or Virginijus Šikšnys should have been properly credited.
[src:nobel-prize/2020-nobel-prizes] Each prize's awarding amount increased from 9 million Swedish krona to 10 million.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The **Nobel Prizes** are awards administered by the Nobel Foundation and granted in accordance with the principle of "for the greatest benefit to humankind".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The prizes were first awarded in 1901, marking the fifth anniversary of Alfred Nobel's death.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The original Nobel Prizes covered five fields: physics, chemistry, physiology or medicine, literature, and peace, specified in Nobel's will.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] A sixth prize, the Prize in Economic Sciences, was established in 1968 by Sveriges Riksbank (Sweden's central bank) in memory of Alfred Nobel.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Prizes are widely regarded as the most prestigious awards available in their respective fields.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Except in extraordinary circumstances, such as war, all six prizes are given annually.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Each recipient, known as a laureate, receives a green gold medal plated with 24 karat gold, a diploma, and a monetary award.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] As of 2023, the Nobel Prize monetary award is 11,000,000 kr, equivalent to approximately US$1,035,000.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] No more than three individuals may share a prize, although the Nobel Peace Prize can be awarded to organisations of more than three people.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel Prizes are not awarded posthumously, but if a person is awarded a prize and dies before receiving it, the prize is presented.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Between 1901 and 2024, the five Nobel Prizes and the Prize in Economic Sciences (since 1969) were awarded 627 times to 1,012 people and organisations.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Five individuals and two organisations have received more than one Nobel Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Alfred Nobel was born on 21 October 1833 in Stockholm, Sweden, into a family of engineers.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] He was a chemist, engineer, and inventor.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1894, Nobel purchased the Bofors iron and steel mill, which he made into a major armaments manufacturer.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This invention was a precursor to many smokeless military explosives, especially the British smokeless powder cordite.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] As a consequence of his patent claims, Nobel was eventually involved in a patent infringement lawsuit over cordite.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel amassed a fortune during his lifetime, with most of his wealth coming from his 355 inventions, of which dynamite is the most famous.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] There is a popular story about how, in 1888, Nobel was astonished to read his own obituary, titled "The Merchant of Death Is Dead", in a French newspaper.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] It was Alfred's brother Ludvig who had died; the obituary was eight years premature.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The article disconcerted Nobel and made him apprehensive about how he would be remembered.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Historians have been unable to verify this story and some dismiss the story as a myth.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] On 10 December 1896, Alfred Nobel died in his villa in San Remo, Italy, from a cerebral haemorrhage.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel wrote several wills during his lifetime.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] He composed the last over a year before he died, signing it at the Swedish–Norwegian Club in Paris on 27 November 1895.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] To widespread astonishment, Nobel's last will specified that his fortune be used to create a series of prizes for those who confer the "greatest benefit on mankind" in physics, chemistry, physiology or medicine, literature, and peace.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel bequeathed 94% of his total assets, 31 million SEK (c.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] US$186 million, €150 million in 2008), to establish the five Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Owing to skepticism surrounding the will, it was not approved by the Storting in Norway until 26 April 1897.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The executors of the will, Ragnar Sohlman and Rudolf Lilljequist, formed the Nobel Foundation to take care of the fortune and to organise the awarding of prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel's instructions named a Norwegian Nobel Committee to award the Peace Prize, the members of which were appointed shortly after the will was approved in April 1897.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Soon thereafter, the other prize-awarding organisations were designated.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] These were the Karolinska Institute on 7 June, the Swedish Academy on 9 June, and the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences on 11 June.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Foundation reached an agreement on guidelines for how the prizes should be awarded; and, in 1900, the Nobel Foundation's newly created statutes were promulgated by King Oscar II.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] According to his will and testament read in Stockholm on 30 December 1896, a foundation established by Alfred Nobel would reward those who serve humanity.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Prize was funded by Alfred Nobel's personal fortune.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] According to the official sources, Alfred Nobel bequeathed most of his fortune to the Nobel Foundation that now forms the economic base of the Nobel Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Foundation was founded as a private organisation on 29 June 1900.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Its function is to manage the finances and administration of the Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In accordance with Nobel's will, the primary task of the foundation is to manage the fortune left to posterity by Nobel.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Robert and Ludvig Nobel were involved in the oil business in Azerbaijan, and according to Swedish historian E.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Bargengren, who accessed the Nobel family archive, it was this "decision to allow withdrawal of Alfred's money from Baku that became the decisive factor that enabled the Nobel Prizes to be established".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Another important task of the Nobel Foundation is to market the prizes internationally and to oversee informal administration related to the prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The foundation is not involved in the process of selecting the Nobel laureates.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In many ways, the Nobel Foundation is similar to an investment company, in that it invests Nobel's money to create a solid funding base for the prizes and the administrative activities.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Foundation is exempt from all taxes in Sweden (since 1946) and from investment taxes in the United States (since 1953).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Since the 1980s, the foundation's investments have become more profitable and as of 31 December 2007, the assets controlled by the Nobel Foundation amounted to 3.628 billion Swedish *kronor* (c.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] According to the statutes, the foundation consists of a board of five Swedish or Norwegian citizens, with its seat in Stockholm.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The chairman of the board is appointed by the Swedish King in Council, with the other four members appointed by the trustees of the prize-awarding institutions.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] An executive director is chosen from among the board members, a deputy director is appointed by the King in Council, and two deputies are appointed by the trustees.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] However, since 1995, all the members of the board have been chosen by the trustees, and the executive director and the deputy director appointed by the board itself.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] As well as the board, the Nobel Foundation is made up of the prize-awarding institutions (the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, the Nobel Assembly at Karolinska Institute, the Swedish Academy, and the Norwegian Nobel Committee), the trustees of these institutions, and auditors.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The capital of the Nobel Foundation today is invested 50% in shares, 20% bonds and 30% other investments (e.g. hedge funds or real estate).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The distribution can vary by 10 percent.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] At the beginning of 2008, 64% of the funds were invested mainly in American and European stocks, 20% in bonds, plus 12% in real estate and hedge funds.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 2011, the total annual cost was approximately 120 million kronor, with 50 million kronor as the prize money.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Further costs to pay institutions and persons engaged in giving the prizes were 27.4 million kronor.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The events during the Nobel week in Stockholm and Oslo cost 20.2 million kronor.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The administration, Nobel symposium, and similar items had costs of 22.4 million kronor.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The cost of the Economic Sciences prize of 16.5 Million kronor is paid by the Sveriges Riksbank.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Once the Nobel Foundation and its guidelines were in place, the Nobel Committees began collecting nominations for the inaugural prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Subsequently, they sent a list of preliminary candidates to the prize-awarding institutions.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Committee's Physics Prize shortlist cited Wilhelm Röntgen's discovery of X-rays and Philipp Lenard's work on cathode rays.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Academy of Sciences selected Röntgen for the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In the last decades of the 19th century, many chemists had made significant contributions.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Thus, with the Chemistry Prize, the academy "was chiefly faced with merely deciding the order in which these scientists should be awarded the prize".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The academy received 20 nominations, eleven of them for Jacobus van 't Hoff.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Van 't Hoff was awarded the prize for his contributions in chemical thermodynamics.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Swedish Academy chose the poet Sully Prudhomme for the first Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] A group including 42 Swedish writers, artists, and literary critics protested against this decision, having expected Leo Tolstoy to be awarded.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Some, including Burton Feldman, have criticised this prize because they consider Prudhomme a mediocre poet.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Feldman's explanation is that most of the academy members preferred Victorian literature and thus selected a Victorian poet.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The first Physiology or Medicine Prize went to the German physiologist and microbiologist Emil von Behring.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] During the 1890s, von Behring developed an antitoxin to treat diphtheria, which until then had been causing thousands of deaths each year.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1938 and 1939, Adolf Hitler's Third Reich forbade three laureates from Germany (Richard Kuhn, Adolf Friedrich Johann Butenandt, and Gerhard Domagk) from accepting their prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] They were all later able to receive the diploma and medal.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Even though Sweden was officially neutral during the Second World War, the prizes were awarded irregularly.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1939, the Peace Prize was not awarded.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] No prize was awarded in any category from 1940 to 1942, due to the occupation of Norway by Germany.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In the subsequent year, all prizes were awarded except those for literature and peace.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] During the occupation of Norway, three members of the Norwegian Nobel Committee fled into exile.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The remaining members escaped persecution from the Germans when the Nobel Foundation stated that the committee building in Oslo was Swedish property.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Thus it was a safe haven from the German military, which was not at war with Sweden.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] These members kept the work of the committee going, but did not award any prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1944, the Nobel Foundation, together with the three members in exile, made sure that nominations were submitted for the Peace Prize and that the prize could be awarded once again.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] After World War II, economics evolved rapidly as an academic discipline and came to be increasingly recognized as a significant scientific field.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1968, Sweden's central bank, Sveriges Riksbank, celebrated its 300th anniversary and donated a sum of money to the Nobel Foundation to be used to set up a new award in the field of economic sciences.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The following year, 1969, the Prize in Economic Sciences was awarded for the first time.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences is required to select the economics laureate in the same way as it does for the science Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The first laureates for the Economics Prize were Jan Tinbergen and Ragnar Frisch, "for having developed and applied dynamic models for the analysis of economic processes".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The board of the Nobel Foundation decided that after this addition, it would allow no further new prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The award process is similar for all of the Nobel Prizes, the main difference being who can make nominations for each of them.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nomination forms are sent by the Nobel Committee to about 3,000 individuals, usually in September the year before the prizes are awarded.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] These individuals are generally prominent academics working in a relevant area.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Regarding the Peace Prize, inquiries are also sent to governments, former Peace Prize laureates, and current or former members of the Norwegian Nobel Committee.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The deadline for the return of the nomination forms is 31 January of the year of the award.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Committee nominates about 300 potential laureates from these forms and additional names.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The nominees are not publicly named, nor are they told that they are being considered for the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] All nomination records for a prize are sealed for 50 years from the awarding of the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Committee then prepares a report reflecting the advice of experts in the relevant fields.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This, along with the list of preliminary candidates, is submitted to the prize-awarding institutions.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The institutions meet to choose the laureate or laureates in each field by a majority vote.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Their decision, which cannot be appealed, is announced immediately after the vote.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] A maximum of three laureates and two different works may be selected per award.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Except for the Peace Prize, which can be awarded to institutions, the awards can only be given to individuals.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The winners are announced by the awarding institutions during the first two weeks of October.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Although posthumous nominations are not presently permitted, individuals who died in the months between their nomination and the decision of the prize committee were originally eligible to receive the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This has occurred twice: the 1931 Literature Prize awarded to Erik Axel Karlfeldt, and the 1961 Peace Prize awarded to UN Secretary General Dag Hammarskjöld.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Since 1974, laureates must be thought alive at the time of the October announcement.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] There has been one laureate, William Vickrey, who in 1996 died after the prize (in Economics) was announced but before it could be presented.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] On 3 October 2011, the laureates for the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine were announced; however, the committee was not aware that one of the laureates, Ralph M.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The committee reconsidered Steinman's award, since the rule is that the prize is not awarded posthumously, but decided that as the decision to award Steinman the prize "was made in good faith", it would remain unchanged, and the prize would be awarded.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel's will provided for prizes to be awarded in recognition of discoveries made "during the preceding year".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Early on, the awards usually recognised recent discoveries.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] However, some of those early discoveries were later discredited.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] For example, Johannes Fibiger was awarded the 1926 Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his purported discovery of a parasite that caused cancer.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] To avoid repeating this embarrassment, the awards increasingly recognised scientific discoveries that had withstood the test of time.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The interval between the award and the accomplishment it recognises varies from discipline to discipline.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Literature Prize is typically awarded to recognise a cumulative lifetime body of work rather than a single achievement.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Peace Prize can also be awarded for a lifetime body of work.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] For example, 2008 laureate Martti Ahtisaari was awarded for his work to resolve international conflicts.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] However, they can also be awarded for specific recent events.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] For instance, Kofi Annan was awarded the 2001 Peace Prize just four years after becoming the Secretary-General of the United Nations.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Similarly Yasser Arafat, Yitzhak Rabin, and Shimon Peres received the 1994 award, about a year after they successfully concluded the Oslo Accords.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] A controversy was caused by awarding the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize to Barack Obama during his first year as US president.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Awards for physics, chemistry, and medicine are typically awarded once the achievement has been widely accepted.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Sometimes, this takes decades – for example, Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar shared the 1983 Physics Prize for his 1930s work on stellar structure and evolution.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Not all scientists live long enough for their work to be recognised.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Some discoveries can never be considered for a prize if their impact is realised after the discoverers have died.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Except for the Peace Prize, the Nobel Prizes are presented in Stockholm, Sweden, at the annual Prize Award Ceremony on 10 December, the anniversary of Nobel's death.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The recipients' lectures are normally held in the days prior to the award ceremony.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Peace Prize and its recipients' lectures are presented at the annual Prize Award Ceremony in Oslo, Norway, usually on 10 December.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The award ceremonies and the associated banquets are typically major international events.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Prizes awarded in Sweden's ceremonies are held at the Stockholm Concert Hall, with the Nobel banquet following immediately at Stockholm City Hall.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Peace Prize ceremony has been held at the Norwegian Nobel Institute (1905–1946), at the auditorium of the University of Oslo (1947–1989), and at Oslo City Hall (1990–present).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The highlight of the Nobel Prize Award Ceremony in Stockholm occurs when each Nobel laureate steps forward to receive the prize from the hands of the King of Sweden.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In Oslo, the chairman of the Norwegian Nobel Committee presents the Nobel Peace Prize in the presence of the King of Norway and the Norwegian royal family.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] At first, King Oscar II did not approve of awarding grand prizes to foreigners.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] After the award ceremony in Sweden, a banquet is held in the Blue Hall at the Stockholm City Hall, which is attended by the Swedish Royal Family and around 1,300 guests.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Peace Prize banquet is held in Norway at the Oslo Grand Hotel after the award ceremony.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Apart from the laureate, guests include the president of the Storting, on occasion the Swedish prime minister, and, since 2006, the King and Queen of Norway.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] According to the statutes of the Nobel Foundation, each laureate is required to give a public lecture on a subject related to the topic of their prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel lecture as a rhetorical genre took decades to reach its current format.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] These lectures normally occur during Nobel Week (the week leading up to the award ceremony and banquet, which begins with the laureates arriving in Stockholm and normally ends with the Nobel banquet), but this is not mandatory.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The laureate is only obliged to give the lecture within six months of receiving the prize, but some have happened even later.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] For example, US President Theodore Roosevelt received the Peace Prize in 1906 but gave his lecture in 1910, after his term in office.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The lectures are organised by the same association which selected the laureates.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] From 1959 to 1990, Swedish journalist Bengt Feldreich gathered the science prize laureates to a discussion, broadcast as *Snillen spekulerar* (in English *Science and Man*) first in radio, and then from the mid-1960s in Sveriges Television.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Since 2004, the program is a coproduction with BBC World News under the title *Nobel Minds*, since 2011 hosted by Zeinab Badawi.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Foundation announced on 30 May 2012 that it had awarded the contract for the production of the five (Swedish) Nobel Prize medals to Svenska Medalj AB.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Between 1902 and 2010, the Nobel Prize medals were minted by Myntverket (the Swedish Mint), which ceased operations in 2011 after 107 years.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 2011, the Mint of Norway, located in Kongsberg, made the medals.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Prize medals are registered trademarks of the Nobel Foundation.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Each medal features an image of Alfred Nobel in left profile on the obverse.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The medals for physics, chemistry, physiology or medicine, and literature have identical obverses, showing the image of Alfred Nobel and the years of his birth and death.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel's portrait also appears on the obverse of the Peace Prize medal and the medal for the Economics Prize, but with a slightly different design.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] For instance, the laureate's name is engraved on the rim of the Economics medal.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The image on the reverse of a medal varies according to the institution awarding the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The reverse sides of the medals for chemistry and physics share the same design.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] All medals made before 1980 were struck in 23 carat gold.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Since then, they have been struck in 18 carat green gold plated with 24 carat gold.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The weight of each medal varies with the value of gold, but averages about 175 grams (0.386 lb) for each medal.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The diameter is 66 millimetres (2.6 in) and the thickness varies between 5.2 millimetres (0.20 in) and 2.4 millimetres (0.094 in).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Because of the high value of their gold content and tendency to be on public display, Nobel medals are subject to medal theft.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] During World War II, the medals of German scientists Max von Laue and James Franck were sent to Copenhagen for safekeeping.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] When Germany invaded Denmark, Hungarian chemist (and Nobel laureate himself) George de Hevesy dissolved them in aqua regia (nitro-hydrochloric acid), to prevent confiscation by Nazi Germany and to prevent legal problems for the holders.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] After the war, the gold was recovered from solution, and the medals re-cast.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel laureates receive a diploma directly from the hands of the King of Sweden, or in the case of the peace prize, the chairman of the Norwegian Nobel Committee.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Each diploma is uniquely designed by the prize-awarding institutions for the laureates that receive them.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The diploma contains a picture and text in Swedish which states the name of the laureate and normally a citation of why they received the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] None of the Nobel Peace Prize laureates has ever had a citation on their diplomas.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The laureates are given a sum of money when they receive their prizes, in the form of a document confirming the amount awarded.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The amount of prize money depends upon how much money the Nobel Foundation can award each year.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The purse has increased since the 1980s, when the prize money was 880,000 SEK per prize (c.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 2009, the monetary award was 10 million SEK (US$1.4 million).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In June 2012, it was lowered to 8 million SEK.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] If two laureates share the prize in a category, the award grant is divided equally between the recipients.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] If there are three, the awarding committee has the option of dividing the grant equally, or awarding one-half to one recipient and one-quarter to each of the others.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] It is common for recipients to donate prize money to benefit scientific, cultural, or humanitarian causes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] As of 2025, the monetary award per prize category is 11 million Swedish kronor (SEK), equivalent to approximately US$1.035 million.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] International Committee of the Red Cross; received the prize thrice (the only person or entity to have receive more than two Nobel Prizes).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Linus Pauling; received the prize twice.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel Prize in Chemistry (1954) and Nobel Peace Prize (1962).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Frederick Sanger; received the prize twice.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees; received the prize twice.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Karl Barry Sharpless; received the prize twice.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Dag Hammarskjöld; received Nobel Peace Prize (1961).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Steinman; received Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (2011).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Received Nobel Prize in Chemistry (1935).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Received Nobel Prize in Medicine (1947).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Gunnar Myrdal received Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics Sciences (1974), Alva Myrdal received Nobel Peace Prize (1982).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Received Nobel Prize in Medicine (2014).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Esther Duflo, Abhijit Banerjee (along with Michael Kremer).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Received Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics Sciences (2019).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Five people have received two Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Marie Skłodowska-Curie received the Physics Prize in 1903 for her work on radioactivity and the Chemistry Prize in 1911 for the isolation of pure radium, making her the only person to be awarded a Nobel Prize in two different sciences.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Linus Pauling was awarded the 1954 Chemistry Prize for his research into the chemical bond and its application to the structure of complex substances.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Pauling was also awarded the Peace Prize in 1962 for his activism against nuclear weapons, making him the only laureate of two unshared prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] John Bardeen received the Physics Prize twice: in 1956 for the invention of the transistor and in 1972 for the theory of superconductivity.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Frederick Sanger received the prize twice in Chemistry: in 1958 for determining the structure of the insulin molecule and in 1980 for inventing a method of determining base sequences in DNA.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Karl Barry Sharpless was awarded the 2001 Chemistry Prize for his research into chirally catalysed oxidation reactions, and the 2022 Chemistry Prize for click chemistry.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Two organisations have received the Peace Prize multiple times.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The International Committee of the Red Cross received it three times: in 1917 and 1944 for its work during the world wars; and in 1963 during the year of its centenary.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has been awarded the Peace Prize twice for assisting refugees: in 1954 and 1981.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Curie family has received the most prizes, with four prizes awarded to five individual laureates.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Marie Skłodowska-Curie received the prizes in Physics (in 1903) and Chemistry (in 1911).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Her husband, Pierre Curie, shared the 1903 Physics prize with her.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Their daughter, Irène Joliot-Curie, received the Chemistry Prize in 1935 together with her husband Frédéric Joliot-Curie.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In addition, Henry Labouisse, the husband of Marie and Pierre Curie's second daughter Ève Curie, was the director of UNICEF when he accepted the Nobel Peace Prize in 1965 on that organisation's behalf.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Although no family matches the Curie family's record, there have been multiple with two laureates.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to the husband-and-wife team of Gerty Cori and Carl Ferdinand Cori in 1947, and to the husband-and-wife team of May-Britt Moser and Edvard Moser in 2014 (along with John O'Keefe).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Thomson for showing that electrons are particles, and in 1937 by his son, George Paget Thomson, for showing that they also have the properties of waves.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] William Henry Bragg and his son, William Lawrence Bragg, shared the Physics Prize in 1915 for inventing X-ray crystallography.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Niels Bohr was awarded the Physics Prize in 1922, as was his son, Aage Bohr, in 1975.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Physics Prize was awarded to Manne Siegbahn in 1924, followed by his son, Kai Siegbahn, in 1981.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Hans von Euler-Chelpin, who received the Chemistry Prize in 1929, was the father of Ulf von Euler, who was awarded the Physiology or Medicine Prize in 1970.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Raman was awarded the Physics Prize in 1930 and was the uncle of Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar, who was awarded the same prize in 1983.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Arthur Kornberg received the Physiology or Medicine Prize in 1959; Kornberg's son Roger later received the Chemistry Prize in 2006.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Arthur Schawlow received the 1981 Physics prize, and was married to the sister of 1964 Physics laureate Charles Townes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Two members of the Hodgkin family received Nobels in consecutive years: Sir Alan Lloyd Hodgkin shared in the Nobel for Physiology or Medicine in 1963, followed by Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin, the wife of his first cousin, who won solo for Chemistry in 1964.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Jan Tinbergen, who was awarded the first Economics Prize in 1969, was the brother of Nikolaas Tinbergen, who received the 1973 Physiology or Medicine Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Gunnar Myrdal, who was awarded the Economics Prize in 1974, was the husband of Alva Myrdal, Peace Prize laureate in 1982.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Economics laureates Paul Samuelson (1970) and Kenneth Arrow (1972; shared) were brothers-in-law.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Frits Zernike, who was awarded the 1953 Physics Prize, was the great-uncle of 1999 Physics laureate Gerard 't Hooft.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 2019, married couple Abhijit Banerjee and Esther Duflo were awarded the Economics Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Christiane Nüsslein-Volhard was awarded the Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1995, and her nephew Benjamin List received the Chemistry Prize in 2021.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Sune Bergström was awarded the Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1982, and his son Svante Pääbo was awarded the same prize in 2022.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Edwin McMillan, who shared the Prize in Chemistry in 1951, was the uncle of John Clauser, who was awarded the Prize in Physics in 2022.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Among other criticisms, the Nobel Committees have been accused of having a political agenda, and of omitting more deserving candidates.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] They have also been accused of Eurocentrism, especially for the Literature Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Among the most criticised Nobel Peace Prizes was the one awarded to Henry Kissinger and Lê Đức Thọ.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This led to the resignation of two Norwegian Nobel Committee members.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Kissinger and Thọ were awarded the prize for negotiating a ceasefire between North Vietnam and the United States in January 1973 during the Vietnam War.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] However, when the award was announced, both sides were still engaging in hostilities.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Critics sympathetic to the North announced that Kissinger was not a peace-maker but the opposite, responsible for widening the war.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Those hostile to the North and what they considered its deceptive practices during negotiations were deprived of a chance to criticise Lê Đức Thọ, as he declined the award.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Yasser Arafat, Shimon Peres, and Yitzhak Rabin received the Peace Prize in 1994 for their efforts in making peace between Israel and Palestine.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Immediately after the award was announced, one of the five Norwegian Nobel Committee members denounced Arafat as a terrorist and resigned.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Additional misgivings about Arafat were widely expressed in various newspapers.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Another controversial Peace Prize was that awarded to Barack Obama in 2009.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nominations had closed only eleven days after Obama took office as President of the United States, but the actual evaluation occurred over the next eight months.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Obama himself stated that he did not feel deserving of the award, or worthy of the company in which it would place him.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Past Peace Prize laureates were divided, some saying that Obama deserved the award, and others saying he had not secured the achievements to yet merit such an accolade.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Obama's award, along with the previous Peace Prizes for Jimmy Carter and Al Gore, also prompted accusations of a liberal bias.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Aung San Suu Kyi was awarded the Peace Prize in 1991.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] However, in 2015, when she came into power in Myanmar, she was criticized for being silent on human rights violations under her rule and especially over the Rohingya genocide and calls were made to strip her of her Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The award of the 2004 Literature Prize to Elfriede Jelinek drew a protest from a member of the Swedish Academy, Knut Ahnlund.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Ahnlund resigned, alleging that the selection of Jelinek had caused "irreparable damage to all progressive forces, it has also confused the general view of literature as an art".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] He alleged that Jelinek's works were "a mass of text shovelled together without artistic structure".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The 2009 Literature Prize to Herta Müller also generated criticism.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] According to *The Washington Post*, many US literary critics and professors were ignorant of her work.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This made those critics feel the prizes were too Eurocentric.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1949, the neurologist António Egas Moniz received the Physiology or Medicine Prize for his development of the prefrontal lobotomy.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The previous year, Walter Freeman had developed a version of the procedure which was faster and easier to carry out.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Due in part to the publicity surrounding the original procedure, Freeman's procedure was prescribed without due consideration or regard for modern medical ethics.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Endorsed by such influential publications as *The New England Journal of Medicine*, leucotomy or "lobotomy" became so popular that about 5,000 lobotomies were performed in the United States in the three years immediately following Moniz's receipt of the Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Although Mohandas Gandhi, an icon of nonviolence in the 20th century, was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize five times, in 1937, 1938, 1939, 1947, and a few days before he was assassinated on 30 January 1948, he was never awarded the prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1948, the year of Gandhi's death, the Norwegian Nobel Committee decided to make no award that year on the grounds that "there was no suitable living candidate".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1989, this omission was publicly regretted, when the 14th Dalai Lama was awarded the Peace Prize, the chairman of the committee said that it was "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Other high-profile individuals with widely recognised contributions to peace have been overlooked.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 2009, an article in *Foreign Policy* magazine identified seven people who "never won the prize, but should have".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The list consisted of Gandhi, Eleanor Roosevelt, Václav Havel, Ken Saro-Wiwa, Sari Nusseibeh, Corazon Aquino, and Liu Xiaobo.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Liu Xiaobo would go on to win the 2010 Nobel Peace Prize while imprisoned.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1965, UN Secretary General U Thant was informed by the Norwegian Permanent Representative to the UN that he would be awarded that year's prize and asked whether or not he would accept.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] He consulted staff and later replied that he would.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] At the same time, Chairman Gunnar Jahn of the Nobel Peace Prize committee lobbied heavily against giving U Thant the prize and the prize was at the last minute awarded to UNICEF.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The rest of the committee all wanted the prize to go to U Thant, for his work in defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis, ending the war in the Congo, and his ongoing work to mediate an end to the Vietnam War.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The disagreement lasted three years and in 1966 and 1967 no prize was given, with Gunnar Jahn effectively vetoing an award to U Thant.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Literature Prize also has controversial omissions.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Adam Kirsch has suggested that many notable writers have missed out on the award for political or extra-literary reasons.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The heavy focus on European and Swedish authors has been a subject of criticism.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Eurocentric nature of the award was acknowledged by Peter Englund, the 2009 Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, as a problem with the award and was attributed to the tendency for the academy to relate more to European authors.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This tendency towards European authors still leaves many European writers on a list of notable writers that have been overlooked for the Literature Prize, including Leo Tolstoy, Anton Chekhov, J.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Tolkien, Émile Zola, Marcel Proust, Vladimir Nabokov, James Joyce, August Strindberg, Simon Vestdijk, Karel Čapek; the New World's Jorge Luis Borges, Ezra Pound, John Updike, Arthur Miller, Mark Twain; and Africa's Chinua Achebe.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Candidates can receive multiple nominations the same year.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Gaston Ramon received a total of 155 nominations in physiology or medicine from 1930 to 1953, the last year with public nomination data for that award as of 2016.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Pierre Paul Émile Roux received 115 nominations in physiology or medicine, and Arnold Sommerfeld received 84 in physics.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] These are the three most nominated scientists without awards in the data published as of 2016.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Otto Stern received 79 nominations in physics 1925–1943 before being awarded in 1943.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The strict rule against awarding a prize to more than three people is also controversial.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] When a prize is awarded to recognise an achievement by a team of more than three collaborators, one or more will miss out.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] All five physicists arrived at the same conclusion, albeit from different angles.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Hagen contends that an equitable solution is to either abandon the three limit restriction, or expand the time period of recognition for a given achievement to two years.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Similarly, the prohibition of posthumous awards fails to recognise achievements by an individual or collaborator who dies before the prize is awarded.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Economics Prize was not awarded to Fischer Black, who died in 1995, when his co-author Myron Scholes received the honor in 1997 for their landmark work on option pricing along with Robert C.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Merton, another pioneer in the development of valuation of stock options.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In the announcement of the award that year, the Nobel committee prominently mentioned Black's key role.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Political subterfuge may also deny proper recognition.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Lise Meitner and Fritz Strassmann, who co-discovered nuclear fission along with Otto Hahn, may have been denied a share of Hahn's 1944 Nobel Chemistry Award due to having fled Germany when the Nazis came to power.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The Meitner and Strassmann roles in the research was not fully recognised until years later, when they joined Hahn in receiving the 1966 Enrico Fermi Award.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Alfred Nobel left his fortune to finance annual prizes to be awarded "to those who, during the preceding year, shall have conferred the greatest benefit on mankind".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] He stated that the Nobel Prizes in Physics should be given "to the person who shall have made the most important 'discovery' or 'invention' within the field of physics".
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Nobel did not emphasise discoveries, but they have historically been held in higher respect by the Nobel Prize Committee than inventions: 77% of the Physics Prizes have been given to discoveries, compared with only 23% to inventions.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Christoph Bartneck and Matthias Rauterberg, in papers published in *Nature* and *Technoetic Arts*, have argued this emphasis on discoveries has moved the Nobel Prize away from its original intention of rewarding the greatest contribution to society.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In terms of the most prestigious awards in STEM fields, only a small proportion have been awarded to women.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Out of 210 laureates in Physics, 181 in Chemistry and 216 in Medicine between 1901 and 2018, there were only three female laureates in physics, five in chemistry and 12 in medicine.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Despite these factors, Marie Curie is to date the only person awarded Nobel Prizes in two different sciences (Physics in 1903, Chemistry in 1911); she is one of only three people who have received two Nobel Prizes in sciences (see Multiple Laureates above).
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Malala Yousafzai is the youngest person ever to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] When she received it in 2014, she was only 17 years old.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Peter Nobel describes the Bank of Sweden Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel as a "false Nobel prize" that dishonours his relative Alfred Nobel, after whom the prize is named, and considers economics to be a pseudoscience.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Two laureates have voluntarily declined the Nobel Prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] George Bernard Shaw attempted to decline the prize money while accepting the 1925 Literature Prize; eventually it was agreed to use it to found the Anglo-Swedish Literary Foundation.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] During the Third Reich, Adolf Hitler hindered Richard Kuhn, Adolf Butenandt, and Gerhard Domagk from accepting their prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] All of them were awarded their diplomas and gold medals after World War II.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 1958, Boris Pasternak declined his prize for literature due to fear of what the Soviet Union government might do if he travelled to Stockholm to accept his prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Aung San Suu Kyi was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991, but her children accepted the prize because she had been placed under house arrest in Burma; Suu Kyi delivered her speech two decades later, in 2012.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Liu Xiaobo was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2010 while he and his wife were under house arrest in China as political prisoners, and he was unable to accept the prize in his lifetime.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Being a symbol of scientific or literary achievement that is recognisable worldwide, the Nobel Prize is often depicted in fiction.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This includes films such as *The Prize* (1963), *Nobel Son* (2007), and *The Wife* (2017) about fictional Nobel laureates, as well as fictionalised accounts of stories surrounding real prizes such as *Nobel Chor*, a 2012 film based on the theft of Rabindranath Tagore's prize.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] It has also been depicted in television shows such as *The Big Bang Theory*.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The statue and memorial symbol *Planet of Alfred Nobel* was opened in Alfred Nobel University of Economics and Law in Dnipro, Ukraine in 2008.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] On the globe, there are 802 Nobel laureates' reliefs made of a composite alloy obtained when disposing of military strategic missiles.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Despite the symbolism of intellectual achievement, some recipients have embraced unsupported and pseudoscientific concepts, including various health benefits of vitamin C and other dietary supplements, homeopathy, HIV/AIDS denialism, and various claims about race and intelligence.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] This is sometimes referred to as Nobel disease.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] In 2001, Gustavus Adolphus College in St.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] Peter, Minnesota, host of the Nobel Conference, commissioned American composer and alumnus Steve Heitzeg to compose a piece for the 100th anniversary of the Nobel Prizes.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The 75-minute *Nobel Symphony* highlights all the major Nobel Prizes, and includes texts from Nobel laureates such as Pablo Neruda, Albert Camus, Toni Morrison, Amartya Sen, Martin Luther King, Jr., Rigoberta Menchú, Dag Hammarskjöld, and Nelson Mandela.
[src:nobel-prize/nobel-prize] The *Nobel Symphony* premiered at Gustavus Adolphus on October 2, 2001, and was restaged by Philip Brunelle and VocalEssence at Orchestra Hall in Minneapolis, Minnesota on April 18, 2004.
